<TEI.2><TEIHEADER><FILEDESC><TITLESTMT><TITLE TYPE="245">The owl and the nightingale (MS Cotton) [a machine-readable transcription]</TITLE><AUTHOR>Anonymous</AUTHOR></TITLESTMT><EDITIONSTMT><EDITION>The electronic text was created from an edited version of  the Cotton manuscript</EDITION></EDITIONSTMT><EXTENT>ca. 80 kilobytes</EXTENT><PUBLICATIONSTMT><DISTRIBUTOR>University of Michigan, Humanities Text Initiative</DISTRIBUTOR><IDNO>OwlC</IDNO><AVAILABILITY><P>Available at URL http://www.hti.umich.edu/english/mideng/</P><P>This text has been made available through the Oxford Text Archive for personal scholarly use only.  OTA number:  U-1684-A</P></AVAILABILITY><DATE>1993</DATE></PUBLICATIONSTMT><SOURCEDESC DEFAULT="NO"><BIBLFULL DEFAULT="NO"><TITLESTMT><TITLE>The owl and the nightingale</TITLE><RESPSTMT><RESP>edited with introduction, texts, notes,  translation, and glossary</RESP><NAME>J.W.H. Atkins</NAME></RESPSTMT></TITLESTMT><EXTENT>xc, 231 p. : ill. ; 23 cm.</EXTENT><PUBLICATIONSTMT><PUBLISHER>University Press</PUBLISHER><PUBPLACE>Cambridge</PUBPLACE><DATE>1922</DATE></PUBLICATIONSTMT><NOTESSTMT><NOTE PLACE="unspecified" ANCHORED="YES">Texts of the Cotton manuscript and the Jesus College,  Oxford MS 29 on opposite pages</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="unspecified" ANCHORED="YES">Authorship was formerly attributed  to Nicholas de Guildford</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="unspecified" ANCHORED="YES">The printed text contained illustrations  which are not noted in the electronic text</NOTE></NOTESSTMT></BIBLFULL></SOURCEDESC></FILEDESC><PROFILEDESC><CREATION><DATE>1190-1210</DATE></CREATION></PROFILEDESC><REVISIONDESC><CHANGE><DATE>February 18, 1994</DATE><RESPSTMT><NAME>Edward Gaynor</NAME><RESP>University of Virginia Library, Cataloging Services Dept.</RESP></RESPSTMT><ITEM>TEI header revised</ITEM></CHANGE><CHANGE><DATE>January 1994</DATE><RESPSTMT><NAME>David Seaman</NAME><RESP>University of Virginia Library Electronic Text Center</RESP></RESPSTMT><ITEM>Tagging brought into line with the OTA.DTD, and parsed</ITEM></CHANGE><CHANGE><DATE>November 1993</DATE><RESPSTMT><NAME>Jamie L. Spriggs</NAME><RESP>University of Virginia Library Electronic Text Center</RESP></RESPSTMT><ITEM>paginated</ITEM></CHANGE><CHANGE><DATE>August 31, 1993</DATE><RESPSTMT><NAME>Edward Gaynor</NAME><RESP>University of Virginia Library, Cataloging Services Dept.</RESP></RESPSTMT><ITEM>TEI header completed</ITEM></CHANGE><CHANGE><DATE>July 1993</DATE><RESPSTMT><NAME>David Gants</NAME><RESP>University of Virginia Library Electronic Text Center</RESP></RESPSTMT><ITEM>UVa header added</ITEM></CHANGE><CHANGE><DATE>1990 or 1991</DATE><RESPSTMT><NAME>John Price-Wilkin</NAME><RESP>University of Michigan</RESP></RESPSTMT><ITEM>SGML tagging added</ITEM></CHANGE></REVISIONDESC></TEIHEADER><TEXT><BODY><HEAD>The Owl and the nightingale (Cotton ms)</HEAD><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 1 through 100</HEAD><PB N="2"><MILESTONE N="233r.1" UNIT="folio"><L>ICH was in one sumere dale,</L><L>in one su&thorn;e di&yogh;ele hale,</L><L>iherde ich holde grete tale</L><L>an hule and one ni&yogh;tingale.</L><L N="5">&THORN;at plait was stif &amp; starc &amp; strong,</L><L>sum wile softe &amp; lud among;</L><L>an ai&thorn;er a&yogh;en o&thorn;er sval,</L><L>&amp; let &thorn;at [vue]le mod ut al.</L><L>&amp; ei&thorn;er seide of o&thorn;eres custe</L><L N="10">&thorn;at alre-worste &thorn;at hi wuste:</L><L>&amp; hure &amp; hure of o&thorn;ere[s] songe</L><L>hi holde plaiding su&thorn;e stronge.</L><L>   &THORN;e ni&yogh;tingale bigon &thorn;e speche,</L><L>in one hurne of one breche, <PB N="4"></L><L N="15">&amp; sat up one vaire bo&yogh;e,</L><L>- &thorn;ar were abute blosme ino&yogh;e,-</L><L>in ore waste &thorn;icke hegge</L><L>imeind mid spire &amp; grene segge.</L><L>Ho was &thorn;e gladur uor &thorn;e rise,</L><L N="20">&amp; song auele cunne wise:</L><L>[b]et &thorn;u&yogh;te &thorn;e dreim &thorn;at he were</L><L>of harpe &amp; pipe &thorn;an he nere:</L><L>bet &thorn;u&yogh;te &thorn;at he were ishote</L><L>of harpe &amp; pipe &thorn;an of &thorn;rote.</L><L N="25">   [&THORN;]o stod on old stoc &thorn;ar biside,</L><L>&thorn;ar &thorn;o vle song hire tide,</L><L>&amp; was mid iui al bigrowe;</L><L>hit was &thorn;are hule earding-stowe.</L><L>   [&THORN;]e ni&yogh;tingale hi ise&yogh;,</L><L N="30">&amp; hi bihold &amp; ouerse&yogh;,</L><L>&amp; &thorn;u&yogh;te wel [vu]l of &thorn;are hule,</L><L>for me hi halt lodlich &amp; fule.</L><L>"Vnwi&yogh;t," ho sede, "awei &thorn;u flo!</L><L>me is &thorn;e w[u]rs &thorn;at ich &thorn;e so. 
<MILESTONE N="233r.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L N="35">Iwis for &thorn;ine [vu]le lete,       </L><L>wel [oft ich] mine song forlete; <PB N="6"></L><L>min horte atfli&thorn; &amp; falt mi tonge,</L><L>wonne &thorn;u art [to me] i&thorn;runge.</L><L>Me luste bet speten &thorn;ane singe</L><L N="40">of &thorn;ine fule &yogh;o&yogh;elinge."</L><L>   &THORN;os hule abod fort hit was eve,</L><L>ho ne mi&yogh;te no leng bileue,</L><L>vor hire horte was so gret</L><L>&thorn;at wel ne&yogh; hire fnast atschet,</L><L N="45">&amp; warp a word &thorn;ar-after longe;</L><L>"Hu &thorn;inc&thorn;e nu bi mine songe?</L><L>We[n]st &thorn;u &thorn;at ich ne cunne singe,</L><L>&thorn;e&yogh; ich ne cunne of writelinge?</L><L>Ilome &thorn;u dest me grame,</L><L N="50">&amp; seist me [bo&thorn;e tone] &amp; schame.</L><L>&YOGH;if ich &thorn;e holde on mine uote,</L><L>(so hit bitide &thorn;at ich mote!)</L><L>&amp; &thorn;u were vt of &thorn;ine rise,</L><L>&thorn;u sholdest singe an o&thorn;er w[i]se."</L><L N="55">   &THORN;e ni&yogh;tingale &yogh;af answare:</L><L>"&YOGH;if ich me loki wit &thorn;e bare,</L><L>&amp; me schilde wit &thorn;e blete,</L><L>ne reche ich no&yogh;t of &thorn;ine &thorn;rete; <PB N="8"></L><L>&yogh;if ich me holde in mine hegge,</L><L N="60">ne recche ich neuer what &thorn;u segge.</L><L>Ich wot &thorn;at &thorn;u art unmilde</L><L>wi&thorn; hom &thorn;at ne mu&yogh;e from [&thorn;]e schilde;</L><L>&amp; &thorn;u tukest wro&thorn;e &amp; vuele,</L><L>whar &thorn;u mi&yogh;t, over smale fu&yogh;ele.</L><L N="65">Vor&thorn;i &thorn;u art lo&thorn; al fuel-kunne,</L><L>&amp; alle ho &thorn;e driue&thorn; honne,</L><L>&amp; &thorn;e bischriche&thorn; &amp; bigredet,</L><L>&amp; wel narewe &thorn;e biledet; 
<MILESTONE N="233v.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>&amp; ek for&thorn;e &thorn;e sulue mose,</L><L N="70">hire &thorn;onkes, wolde &thorn;e totose.</L><L>&thorn;u art lodlich to biholde,</L><L>&amp; &thorn;u art lo&thorn; in monie volde;</L><L>&thorn;i bodi is short, &thorn;i swore is smal,</L><L>grettere is &thorn;in heued &thorn;an &thorn;u al;</L><L N="75">&thorn;in e&yogh;ene bo&thorn; col-blake &amp; brode,</L><L>ri&yogh;t swo ho weren ipeint mid wode;</L><L>&thorn;u starest so &thorn;u wille abiten</L><L>al &thorn;at &thorn;u mi[&yogh;]t mid cliure smiten:</L><L>&thorn;i bile is stif &amp; scharp &amp; hoked,</L><L N="80">ri&yogh;t so an owel &thorn;at is croked;</L><L>&thorn;ar-mid &thorn;u clackes[t] oft &amp; longe,</L><L>&amp; &thorn;at is on of &thorn;ine songe.</L><L>Ac &thorn;u &thorn;retest to mine fleshe,</L><L>mid &thorn;ine cliures woldest me meshe.</L><L N="85">&thorn;e were icundur to one frogge</L><L> *     *     *     *     * <PB N="10"></L><L>snailes, mus, &amp; fule wi&yogh;te,</L><L>bo&thorn; &thorn;ine cunde &amp; &thorn;ine ri&yogh;te.</L><L>&THORN;u sittest adai &amp; fli&yogh;[s]t ani&yogh;t,</L><L N="90">&thorn;u cu&thorn;est &thorn;at &thorn;u art on vnwi&yogh;t.</L><L>&THORN;u art lodlich &amp; unclene,</L><L>bi &thorn;ine neste ich hit mene,</L><L>&amp; ek bi &thorn;ine fule brode,</L><L>&thorn;u fedest on hom a wel ful fode.</L><L N="95">Vel wostu &thorn;at hi do&thorn; &thorn;arinne,</L><L>hi fule&thorn; hit up to &thorn;e chinne:</L><L>ho sitte&thorn; &thorn;ar so hi bo bisne.</L><L>&THORN;arbi men segget a uorbisne:</L><L>"Dahet habbe &thorn;at ilke best</L><L N="100">&thorn;at fule&thorn; his owe nest."</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 101 through 200</HEAD><L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er &yogh;er a faukun bredde;</L><L>his nest no&yogh;t wel he ne bihedde:</L><L>&thorn;arto &thorn;u stele in o dai, <MILESTONE N="233v.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>&amp; leidest &thorn;aron &thorn;i fole ey.</L><L N="105">&THORN;o hit bicom &thorn;at he ha&yogh;te,</L><L>&amp; of his eyre briddes wra&yogh;te;</L><L>ho bro&yogh;te his briddes mete,</L><L>bihold his nest, ise&yogh; hi ete: <PB N="12"></L><L>he ise&yogh; bi one halue</L><L N="110">his nest ifuled uthalue.</L><L>&THORN;e faucun was wro&thorn; wit his bridde,</L><L>&amp; lude &yogh;al &amp; sterne chidde:</L><L>"Segget me, wo hauet &thorn;is ido?</L><L>Ov nas neuer icunde &thorn;arto:</L><L N="115">hit was idon ov a lo&thorn;[e] [cu]ste.</L><L>Segge[&thorn;] me &yogh;if &yogh;e hit wiste."</L><L>&THORN;o qua&thorn; &thorn;at on &amp; quad &thorn;at o&thorn;er:</L><L>"Iwis it was ure o&yogh;er bro&thorn;er,</L><L>&thorn;e &yogh;ond &thorn;at haue[&thorn;] &thorn;at grete heued:</L><L N="120">wai &thorn;at hi[t] nis &thorn;arof bireued!</L><L>Worp hit ut mid &thorn;e alre-[vu]rste</L><L>&thorn;at his necke him to-berste!"</L><L>&THORN;e faucun ilefde his bridde,</L><L>&amp; nom &thorn;at fule brid amidde,</L><L N="125">&amp; warp hit of &thorn;an wilde bowe,</L><L>&thorn;ar pie &amp; crowe hit todrowe.</L><L>Herbi men segget a bispel,</L><L>&thorn;e&yogh; hit ne bo fuliche spel;</L><L>al so hit is bi &thorn;an ungode</L><L N="130">&thorn;at is icumen of fule brode, <PB N="14"></L><L>&amp; is meind wit fro monne,</L><L>euer he cu&thorn; &thorn;at he com &thorn;onne,</L><L>&thorn;at he com of &thorn;an adel-eye,</L><L>&thorn;e&yogh; he a fro nest[e] leie.</L><L N="135">&thorn;e&yogh; appel trendli fro[m] &thorn;on trowe,</L><L>&thorn;ar he &amp; o&thorn;er mid growe,</L><L>&thorn;e&yogh; he bo &thorn;ar-from bicume, 
<MILESTONE N="234r.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>he cu&thorn; wel whonene he is icume."</L><L>   &THORN;os word a&yogh;af &thorn;e ni&yogh;tingale,</L><L N="140">&amp; after &thorn;are longe tale</L><L>he song so lude &amp; so scharpe,</L><L>ri&yogh;t so me grulde schille harpe.</L><L>&THORN;os hule luste &thorn;iderward,</L><L>&amp; hold hire e&yogh;e no&thorn;erwa[r]d,</L><L N="145">&amp; sat tosvolle &amp; ibolwe,</L><L>also ho hadde one frogge isuol&yogh;e:</L><L>for ho wel wiste &amp; was iwar</L><L>&thorn;at ho song hire a-bisemar.</L><L>&amp; no&thorn;eles ho &yogh;a[f] andsuare,</L><L N="150">"Whi neltu flon into &thorn;e bare, <PB N="16"></L><L>&amp; sewi [w]are unker bo</L><L>of bri&yogh;ter howe, of uairur blo?"</L><L>"No, &thorn;u hauest wel scharpe clawe,</L><L>ne kepich no&yogh;t &thorn;at &thorn;u me clawe.</L><L N="155">&thorn;u hauest cliuers su&thorn;e stronge,</L><L>&thorn;u tuengst &thorn;ar-mid so do&thorn; a tonge.</L><L>&THORN;u &thorn;o&yogh;test, so do&thorn; &thorn;ine ilike,</L><L>mid faire worde me biswike.</L><L>Ich nolde don &thorn;at &thorn;u me raddest,</L><L N="160">ich wiste wel &thorn;at &thorn;u me misraddest.</L><L>Schamie &thorn;e for &thorn;in unrede!</L><L>Vnwro&yogh;en is &thorn;i svikelhede!</L><L>Schild &thorn;ine svikeldom vram &thorn;e li&yogh;te,</L><L>&amp; hud &thorn;at wo&yogh;e amon[g] &thorn;e ri&yogh;te.</L><L N="165">&THORN;ane &thorn;u wilt &thorn;in unri&yogh;t spene,</L><L>loke &thorn;at hit ne bo isene:</L><L>vor svikedom haue[&thorn;] schome &amp; hete,</L><L>&yogh;if hit is ope &amp; under&yogh;ete.</L><L>Ne speddestu no&yogh;t mid &thorn;ine unwrenche,</L><L N="170">for ich am war &amp; can wel blenche.</L><L>Ne help&thorn; no&yogh;t &thorn;at &thorn;u bo to [&thorn;]riste: 
<MILESTONE N="234r.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>ich wolde vi&yogh;te bet mid liste <PB N="18"></L><L>&thorn;an &thorn;u mid al &thorn;ine streng&thorn;e.</L><L>Ich habbe, on brede &amp; eck on leng&thorn;e,</L><L N="175">castel god on mine rise:</L><L>"Wel fi&yogh;t &thorn;at wel fli&yogh;t," sei&thorn; &thorn;e wise.</L><L>Ac lete we awei &thorn;os cheste,</L><L>vor suiche wordes bo&thorn; unw[re]ste;</L><L>&amp; fo we on mid ri&yogh;te dome,</L><L N="180">mid faire worde &amp; mid ysome.</L><L>&THORN;e&yogh; we ne bo at one acorde,</L><L>we m[a]&yogh;e bet mid fayre worde,</L><L>witute cheste, &amp; bute fi&yogh;te,</L><L>plaidi mid fo&yogh;e &amp; mid ri&yogh;te:</L><L N="185">&amp; mai hure ei&thorn;er wat h[e] wile</L><L>mid ri&yogh;te segge &amp; mid sckile."</L><L>   &THORN;o qua&thorn; &thorn;e hule "[W]u schal us seme,</L><L>&thorn;at kunne &amp; wille ri&yogh;t us deme?"</L><L>"Ich wot wel" qua&thorn; &thorn;e ni&yogh;tingale,</L><L N="190">"Ne &thorn;aref &thorn;arof bo no tale.</L><L>Maister Nichole of Guldeforde,</L><L>he is wis an war of worde:</L><L>he is of dome su&thorn;e gleu,</L><L>&amp; him is lo&thorn; eurich un&thorn;eu. <PB N="20"></L><L N="195">He wot insi&yogh;t in eche songe,</L><L>wo singet wel, wo singet wronge:</L><L>&amp; he can schede vrom &thorn;e ri&yogh;te</L><L>&thorn;at wo&yogh;e, &thorn;at &thorn;uster from &thorn;e li&yogh;te."</L><L>   &THORN;o hule one wile hi bi&thorn;o&yogh;te,</L><L N="200">&amp; after &thorn;an &thorn;is word upbro&yogh;te:</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 201 through 300</HEAD><L>"Ich granti wel &thorn;at he us deme,</L><L>vor &thorn;e&yogh; he were wile breme,</L><L>&amp; lof him were ni&yogh;tingale,</L><L>&amp; o&thorn;er wi&yogh;te gente &amp; smale,</L><L N="205">ich wot he is nu su&thorn;e acoled. <MILESTONE N="234v.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>Nis he vor &thorn;e no&yogh;t afoled,</L><L>&thorn;at he, for &thorn;ine olde luue,</L><L>me adun legge &amp; &thorn;e buue:</L><L>ne schaltu neure so him queme,</L><L N="210">&thorn;at he for &thorn;e fals dom deme.</L><L>He is him ripe &amp; fast-rede,</L><L>ne lust him nu to none unrede:</L><L>nu him ne lust na more pleie,</L><L>he wile gon a ri&yogh;te weie."</L><L N="215">   &THORN;e ni&yogh;tingale was al &yogh;are,</L><L>ho hadde ilorned wel aiware:</L><L>"Hule," ho sede, "seie me so&thorn;,</L><L>wi dostu &thorn;at unwi&yogh;tis do&thorn;?</L><L>&thorn;u singist ani&yogh;t &amp; no&yogh;t adai,</L><L N="220">&amp; al &thorn;i song is wailawai. <PB N="22"></L><L>&THORN;u mi&yogh;t mid &thorn;ine songe afere</L><L>alle &thorn;at ihere&thorn; &thorn;ine ibere:</L><L>&thorn;u sch[ri]chest &amp; &yogh;ollest to &thorn;ine fere,</L><L>&thorn;at hit is grislich to ihere:</L><L N="225">hit &thorn;inche[&thorn;] bo&thorn;e wise &amp; snepe</L><L>no&yogh;t &thorn;at &thorn;u singe, ac &thorn;at &thorn;u wepe.</L><L>&THORN;u fli&yogh;st ani&yogh;t &amp; no&yogh;t adai:</L><L>&thorn;arof ich w[u]ndri &amp; wel mai.</L><L>vor eurich &thorn;ing &thorn;at schuniet ri&yogh;t,</L><L N="230">hit luue&thorn; &thorn;uster &amp; hatiet li&yogh;t:</L><L>&amp; eurich &thorn;ing &thorn;at is lof misdede,</L><L>hit luue&thorn; &thorn;uster to his dede.</L><L>A wis word, &thorn;e&yogh; hit bo unclene,</L><L>is fele manne a-mu&thorn;e imene,</L><L N="235">for Alured King hit seide &amp; wrot:</L><L>"He schunet &thorn;at hine [vu]l wot."</L><L>Ich wene &thorn;at &thorn;u dost also,</L><L>vor &thorn;u fli&yogh;st ni&yogh;tes euer mo.</L><L>An o&thorn;er &thorn;ing me is a-wene, 
<MILESTONE N="234v.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L N="240">&thorn;u hauest ani&yogh;t wel bri&yogh;te sene;    </L><L>bi daie &thorn;u art stare-blind,</L><L>&thorn;at &thorn;u ne sichst ne bov ne strind. <PB N="24"></L><L>Adai &thorn;u art blind o&thorn;er bisne,</L><L>&thorn;arbi men segget a uorbisne:</L><L N="245">"Ri&yogh;t so hit far&thorn; bi &thorn;an ungode</L><L>&thorn;at no&yogh;t ne su&thorn; to none gode,</L><L>&amp; is so ful of vuele wrenche</L><L>&thorn;at him ne mai no man atprenche,</L><L>&amp; can wel &thorn;ane &thorn;u[str]e wai,</L><L N="250">&amp; &thorn;ane bri&yogh;te lat awai."</L><L>So do&thorn; &thorn;at bo&thorn; of &thorn;ine cunde,</L><L>of li&yogh;te nabbe&thorn; hi none imunde."</L><L>   &THORN;os hule luste su&thorn;e longe,</L><L>&amp; was oftoned su&thorn;e stronge:</L><L N="255">ho qua&thorn; "&THORN;u [h]attest ni&yogh;tingale,</L><L>&thorn;u mi&yogh;test bet hoten galegale, <PB N="26"></L><L>vor &thorn;u hauest to monie tale.</L><L>Lat &thorn;ine tunge habbe spale!</L><L>&THORN;u wenest &thorn;at &thorn;es dai bo &thorn;in o&yogh;e:</L><L N="260">lat me nu habbe mine &thorn;ro&yogh;e:</L><L>bo nu stille &amp; lat me speke,</L><L>ich wille bon of &thorn;e awreke.</L><L>&amp; lust hu ich con me bitelle,</L><L>mid ri&yogh;te so&thorn;e, witute spelle.</L><L N="265">&THORN;u seist &thorn;at ich me hude adai,</L><L>&thorn;arto ne segge ich nich ne nai:</L><L>&amp; lust ich telle &thorn;e wareuore,</L><L>al wi hit is &amp; wareuore.</L><L>Ich habbe bile stif &amp; stronge,</L><L N="270">&amp; gode cliuers scharp &amp; longe,</L><L>so hit bicume&thorn; to hauekes cunne;</L><L>hit is min hi&yogh;te, hit is mi w[u]nne,</L><L>&thorn;at ich me dra&yogh;e to mine cunde, 
<MILESTONE N="235r.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>ne mai [me] no man &thorn;areuore schende :</L><L N="275">on me hit is wel isene,</L><L>vor ri&yogh;te cunde ich am so kene.</L><L>Vor&thorn;i ich am lo&thorn; smale fo&yogh;le</L><L>&thorn;at flo&thorn; bi grunde an bi &thorn;uuele: <PB N="28"></L><L>hi me bichermet &amp; bigrede&thorn;,</L><L N="280">&amp; hore flockes to [m]e lede&thorn;.</L><L>Me is lof to habbe reste</L><L>&amp; sitte stille in mine neste:</L><L>vor nere ich neuer no &thorn;e betere,</L><L>[&yogh;]if ich mid chauling &amp; mid chatere</L><L N="285">hom schende &amp; mid fule worde,</L><L>so herdes do&thorn; o&thorn;er mid schit-worde.</L><L>Ne lust me wit &thorn;e screwen chide;</L><L>for&thorn;i ich wende from hom wide.</L><L>Hit is a wise monne dome,</L><L N="290">&amp; hi hit segget wel ilome,</L><L>&thorn;at me ne chide wit &thorn;e gidie,</L><L>ne wit &thorn;an ofne me ne &yogh;onie.</L><L>At sume si&thorn;e herde [I] telle</L><L>hu Alured sede on his spelle:</L><L N="295">"Loke &thorn;at &thorn;u ne bo &thorn;are</L><L>&thorn;ar chauling bo&thorn; &amp; cheste &yogh;are:</L><L>lat sottes chide &amp; uor&thorn; &thorn;u go."</L><L>&amp; ich am wis &amp; do also.</L><L>&amp; &yogh;et Alured seide an o&thorn;er side</L><L N="300">a word &thorn;at is isprunge wide:</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 301 through 400</HEAD><L>"&THORN;at wit &thorn;e fule haue&thorn; imene,</L><L>ne cume&thorn; he neuer from him cleine."</L><L>Wenestu &thorn;at haueck bo &thorn;e worse</L><L>&thorn;o&yogh; crowe bigrede him bi &thorn;e mershe, <PB N="30"></L><L N="305">&amp; go&thorn; to him mid hore chirme</L><L>ri&yogh;t so hi wille wit him schirme?</L><L>&THORN;e hauec fol&yogh;e&thorn; gode rede, <MILESTONE N="235r.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>&amp; fli&yogh;t his wei &amp; lat him grede."</L><L>   "&YOGH;et &thorn;u me seist of o&thorn;er &thorn;inge,</L><L N="310">&amp; telst &thorn;at ich ne can no&yogh;t singe,</L><L>ac al mi rorde is woning,</L><L>&amp; to ihire grislich &thorn;ing.</L><L>&THORN;at nis no&yogh;t so&thorn;, ich singe efne,</L><L>mid fulle dreme &amp; lude stefne.</L><L N="315">&THORN;u wenist &thorn;at ech song bo grislich,</L><L>&thorn;at &thorn;ine pipinge nis ilich.</L><L>Mi stefne is [bold] &amp; no&yogh;t unorne,</L><L>ho is ilich one grete horne,</L><L>&amp; &thorn;in is ilich one pipe,</L><L N="320">of one smale wode unripe.</L><L>Ich singe bet &thorn;an &thorn;u dest:</L><L>&thorn;u chaterest so do&thorn; on Irish prost.</L><L>Ich singe an eue a ri&yogh;te time,</L><L>&amp; so&thorn;&thorn;e won hit is bed-time,</L><L N="325">&thorn;e &thorn;ridde si&thorn;e a[t] middel-ni&yogh;te:</L><L>&amp; so ich mine song adi&yogh;te</L><L>wone ich iso arise vorre</L><L>o&thorn;er dai-rim o&thorn;er dai-sterre.</L><L>Ich do god mid mine &thorn;rote,</L><L N="330">&amp; warni men to hore note.</L><L>Ac &thorn;u singest alle longe ni&yogh;t,</L><L>from eue fort hit is dai-li&yogh;t,</L><L>&amp; eure seist &thorn;in o song</L><L>so longe so &thorn;e ni&yogh;t is long:  <PB N="32"></L><L N="335">  &amp; eure crowe&thorn; &thorn;i wrecche crei,</L><L>&thorn;at he ne swike&thorn; ni&yogh;t ne dai.</L><L>Mid &thorn;ine pipinge &thorn;u adunest</L><L>&thorn;as monnes earen &thorn;ar &thorn;u wunest,</L><L>&amp; makest &thorn;ine song so unw[u]r&thorn;</L><L N="340">&thorn;a[t] me ne tel&thorn; of &thorn;ar no&yogh;[t] w[u]r&thorn;.</L><L>Eurich mur&yogh;&thorn;e mai so longe ileste <MILESTONE N="235v.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>&thorn;at ho shal liki wel unwreste:</L><L>vor harpe, &amp; pipe, &amp; fu&yogh;eles [song]</L><L>mislike&thorn;, &yogh;if hit is to long.</L><L N="345">Ne bo &thorn;e song neuer so murie,</L><L>&thorn;at he ne shal &thorn;inche wel unmurie</L><L>&yogh;ef he ileste&thorn; ouer unwille:</L><L>so &thorn;u mi&yogh;t &thorn;ine song aspille.</L><L>Vor hit is so&thorn;, Alured hit seide,</L><L N="350">&amp; me hit mai ine boke rede:</L><L>"Eurich &thorn;ing mai losen his godhede</L><L>mid unme&thorn;e &amp; mid ouerdede."</L><L>Mid este &thorn;u &thorn;e mi&yogh;t ouerquatie,</L><L>&amp; ouerfulle make&thorn; wlatie: <PB N="34"></L><L N="355">an eurich mure&yogh;&thorn;e mai agon</L><L>&yogh;if me hit halt eure for&thorn; in on,</L><L>bute one, &thorn;at is Godes riche,</L><L>&thorn;at eure is svete &amp; eure iliche:</L><L>&thorn;e&yogh; &thorn;u nime eure o[f] &thorn;an lepe,</L><L N="360">hit is eure ful bi hepe.</L><L>Wunder hit is of Godes riche,</L><L>&thorn;at eure spen&thorn; &amp; euer is iliche.</L><L>   &yogh;ut &thorn;u me seist an o&thorn;er shome,</L><L>&thorn;at ich a[m] on mine e&yogh;en lome,</L><L N="365">an seist, for &thorn;at ich flo bi ni&yogh;te,</L><L>&thorn;at ich ne mai iso bi li&yogh;te.</L><L>&THORN;u liest! on me hit is isene</L><L>&thorn;at ich habbe gode sene:</L><L>vor nis non so dim &thorn;usternesse</L><L N="370">&thorn;at ich euer iso &thorn;e lasse.</L><L>&THORN;u wenest &thorn;at ich ne mi&yogh;te iso,</L><L>vor ich bi daie no&yogh;t ne flo.</L><L>&THORN;e hare lute&thorn; al dai,</L><L>ac no&thorn;eles iso he mai.</L><L N="375">&YOGH;if hundes urne&thorn; to him-ward, 
<MILESTONE N="235v.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>[h]e geng&thorn; wel sui&thorn;e awai-ward,</L><L>&amp; hoke&thorn; pa&thorn;es svi&thorn;e narewe,</L><L>&amp; haue&thorn; mid him his blenches &yogh;arewe,</L><L>&amp; hup&thorn; &amp; star[t] su&thorn;e coue,</L><L N="380">an seche&thorn; pa&thorn;es to &thorn;e groue:</L><L>ne sholde he uor bo&thorn;e his e&yogh;e</L><L>so don, &yogh;if he &thorn;e bet nise&yogh;e. <PB N="36"></L><L>Ich mai ison so wel so on hare,</L><L>&thorn;e&yogh; ich bi daie sitte an dare.</L><L N="385">&THORN;ar a&yogh;te men [bo&thorn;] in worre,</L><L>an fare&thorn; bo&thorn;e ner an forre,</L><L>an oueruare&thorn; fele [&thorn;]ode,</L><L>an do&thorn; bi ni&yogh;te gode node,</L><L>ich fol&yogh;i &thorn;an a&yogh;te manne,</L><L N="390">an flo bi ni&yogh;te in hore banne."</L><L>   &THORN;e ni&yogh;tingale in hire &thorn;o&yogh;te</L><L>athold al &thorn;is, &amp; longe &thorn;o&yogh;te</L><L>wat ho &thorn;arafter mi&yogh;te segge:</L><L>vor ho ne mi&yogh;te no&yogh;t alegge</L><L N="395">&thorn;at &thorn;e hule hadde hire ised,</L><L>vor he spac bo&thorn;e ri&yogh;t an red.</L><L>An hire of&thorn;u&yogh;te &thorn;at ho hadde</L><L>&thorn;e speche so for uor&thorn; iladde,</L><L>an was oferd &thorn;at hire answare</L><L N="400">ne w[u]r&thorn;e no&yogh;t ari&yogh;t ifare.</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 401 through 500</HEAD><L>Ac no&thorn;eles he spac boldeliche,</L><L>vor he is wis &thorn;at hardeliche</L><L>wi&thorn; is uo ber&thorn; grete ilete,</L><L>&thorn;at he uor are&yogh;&thorn;e hit ne forlete: <PB N="38"></L><L N="405">vor suich wor&thorn; bold &yogh;if &thorn;u [fli&yogh;st],</L><L>&thorn;at w[u]le flo &yogh;if &thorn;u [n]isvicst;</L><L>&yogh;if he isi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;u nart are&yogh;,</L><L>he wile of [bore] w[u]rchen bare&yogh;.</L><L>&amp; for&thorn;i, &thorn;e&yogh; &thorn;e ni&yogh;tingale <MILESTONE N="236r.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L N="410">were aferd, ho spac bolde tale.   </L><L>   "[H]ule" ho seide " wi dostu so?</L><L>&thorn;u singest a-winter wolawo!</L><L>&thorn;u singest so do&thorn; hen a-snowe,</L><L>al &thorn;at ho singe&thorn; hit is for wowe.</L><L N="415">A-wintere &thorn;u singest wro&thorn;e &amp; &yogh;omere,</L><L>an eure &thorn;u art dumb a-sumere.</L><L>Hit is for &thorn;ine fule ni&thorn;e</L><L>&thorn;at &thorn;u ne mi&yogh;t mid us bo bli&thorn;e,</L><L>vor &thorn;u forbernest wel ne&yogh; for onde</L><L N="420">wane ure blisse cume&thorn; to londe.</L><L>&thorn;u farest so do&thorn; &thorn;e ille,</L><L>evrich blisse him is unwille:</L><L>grucching &amp; luring him bo&thorn; rade,</L><L>&yogh;if he iso&thorn; &thorn;at men bo&thorn; glade. <PB N="40"></L><L N="425">He wolde &thorn;at he ise&yogh;e</L><L>teres in evrich monnes e&yogh;e:</L><L>ne ro&yogh;te he &thorn;e&yogh; flockes were</L><L>imeind bi toppes &amp; bi here.</L><L>Al so &thorn;u dost on &thorn;ire side:</L><L N="430">vor wanne snov li&thorn; &thorn;icke &amp; wide,</L><L>an alle wi&yogh;tes habbe&thorn; sor&yogh;e,</L><L>&thorn;u singest from eue fort a-mor&yogh;e.</L><L>Ac ich alle blisse mid me bringe:</L><L>ech wi&yogh;t is glad for mine &thorn;inge,</L><L N="435">&amp; blisse&thorn; hit wanne ich cume,</L><L>&amp; hi&yogh;te&thorn; a&yogh;en mine kume.</L><L>&THORN;e blostme ginne&thorn; springe &amp; sprede,</L><L>bo&thorn;e ine tro &amp; ek on mede.</L><L>&THORN;e lilie mid hire faire wlite</L><L N="440">wolcume&thorn; me, &thorn;at &thorn;u hit w[i]te,</L><L>bit me mid hire faire blo</L><L>&thorn;at ich shulle to hire flo. <PB N="42"></L><L>&THORN;e rose also mid hire rude, 
<MILESTONE N="236r.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>&thorn;at cume&thorn; ut of &thorn;e &thorn;orne wode,</L><L N="445">bit me &thorn;at ich shulle singe</L><L>vor hire luue one skentinge:</L><L>&amp; ich so do &thorn;ur&yogh; ni&yogh;t &amp; dai,</L><L>&thorn;e more ich singe &thorn;e more I mai,</L><L>an skente hi mid mine songe,</L><L N="450">ac no&thorn;eles no&yogh;t ouerlonge;</L><L>wane ich iso &thorn;at men bo&thorn; glade,</L><L>ich nelle &thorn;at hi bon to sade:</L><L>&thorn;an is ido vor wan ich com,</L><L>ich fare a&yogh;en &amp; do wisdom.</L><L N="455">Wane mon ho&yogh;e&thorn; of his sheue,</L><L>an falewi cume&thorn; on grene leue,</L><L>ich fare hom &amp; nime leue:</L><L>ne recche ich no&yogh;t of winteres reue.</L><L>wan ich iso &thorn;at cume&thorn; &thorn;at harde,</L><L N="460">ich fare hom to min erde,</L><L>an habbe bo&thorn;e luue &amp; &thorn;onc</L><L>&thorn;at ich her com &amp; hider swonk.</L><L>&THORN;an min erende is ido,</L><L>sholde ich bileue? nai, [w]arto?</L><L N="465">vor he nis no&thorn;er &yogh;ep ne wis,</L><L>&thorn;at longe abid &thorn;ar him nod nis."</L><L>   &THORN;os hule luste, &amp; leide an hord</L><L>al &thorn;is mot, word after word,</L><L>an after &thorn;o&yogh;te hu he mi&yogh;te</L><L N="470">ansvere uinde best mid ri&yogh;te:</L><L>vor he mot hine ful wel bi&thorn;enche,</L><L>&thorn;at is aferd of plaites wrenche.</L><L>   "&THORN;v aishest me," &thorn;e hule sede,</L><L>"wi ich a-winter singe &amp; grede. <PB N="44"></L><L N="475">Hit is gode monne iwone,</L><L>an was from &thorn;e worlde frome,</L><L>&thorn;at ech god man his frond icnowe, 
<MILESTONE N="236v.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>an blisse mid hom sume &thorn;rowe</L><L>in his huse at his borde,</L><L N="480">mid faire speche &amp; faire worde.</L><L>&amp; hure &amp; hure to Cristesmasse,</L><L>&thorn;ane riche &amp; poure, more &amp; lasse,</L><L>singe&thorn; cundut ni&yogh;t &amp; dai,</L><L>ich hom helpe what ich mai.</L><L N="485">&amp; ek ich &thorn;enche of o&thorn;er &thorn;inge</L><L>&thorn;ane to pleien o&thorn;er to singe.</L><L>Ich habbe herto gode ansuare</L><L>anon iredi &amp; al &yogh;are:</L><L>vor sumeres-tide is al to [w]lonc,</L><L N="490">an do&thorn; misreken monnes &thorn;onk:</L><L>vor he ne rec&thorn; no&yogh;t of clennesse,</L><L>al his &thorn;o&yogh;t is of golnesse:</L><L>vor none dor no leng nabide&thorn;,</L><L>ac eurich upon o&thorn;er ride&thorn;:</L><L N="495">&thorn;e sulue stottes ine &thorn;e stode</L><L>bo&thorn; bo&thorn;e wilde &amp; mere-wode.</L><L>&amp; &thorn;u sulf art &thorn;ar-among,</L><L>for of golnesse is al &thorn;i song,</L><L>an a&yogh;en &thorn;et &thorn;u w[i]lt teme,</L><L N="500">&thorn;u art wel modi &amp; wel breme.</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 501 through 600</HEAD><L>Sone so &thorn;u hau[e]st itrede,</L><L>ne mi&yogh;tu leng a word ique&thorn;e,</L><L>ac pipest al so do&thorn; a mose,</L><L>mid chokeringe, mid steune hose. <PB N="46"></L><L N="505">&yogh;et &thorn;u singst worse &thorn;on &thorn;e heisugge,</L><L>[&thorn;]at fli&YOGH;&thorn; bi grunde among &thorn;e stubbe:</L><L>wane &thorn;i lust is ago,</L><L>&thorn;onne is &thorn;i song ago also.</L><L>A-sumere chorles awede&thorn;</L><L N="510">&amp; uorcrempe&thorn; &amp; uorbrede&thorn;:</L><L>hit nis for luue no&thorn;eles,</L><L>ac is &thorn;e chorles wode res; <MILESTONE N="236v.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>vor wane he haue&thorn; ido his dede,</L><L>ifallen is al his boldhede,</L><L N="515">habbe he istunge under gore,</L><L>ne last his luue no leng more.</L><L>Al so hit is on &thorn;ine mode:</L><L>so sone so &thorn;u sittest a-brode,</L><L>&thorn;u forlost al &thorn;ine wise.</L><L N="520">Al so &thorn;u farest on &thorn;ine rise:</L><L>wane &thorn;u hauest ido &thorn;i gome,</L><L>&thorn;i steune go&thorn; anon to shome.</L><L>Ac [w]ane ni&yogh;tes cume&thorn; longe,</L><L>&amp; b[r]inge&thorn; forstes starke an stronge,</L><L N="525">&thorn;anne erest hit is isene</L><L>war is &thorn;e snelle, [w]ar is &thorn;e kene.</L><L>At &thorn;an harde me mai auinde</L><L>[w]o ge&thorn; for&thorn;, wo li&thorn; bihinde.</L><L>Me mai ison at &thorn;are node,</L><L N="530">[w]an me shal harde wike bode; <PB N="48"></L><L>&thorn;anne ich am snel &amp; pleie &amp; singe,</L><L>&amp; hi&yogh;te me mid mi skentinge:</L><L>of none wintere ich ne recche,</L><L>vor ich nam non asv[u]nde wrecche.</L><L N="535">&amp; ek ich frouri uele wi&yogh;te</L><L>&thorn;at mid hom nabbe[&thorn;] none mi&yogh;tte:</L><L>hi bo&thorn; ho&yogh;fule &amp; uel arme,</L><L>an seche&thorn; &yogh;orne to &thorn;e warme;</L><L>oft ich singe uor hom &thorn;e more</L><L N="540">for lutli sum of hore sore.</L><L>Hu &thorn;inc&thorn; &thorn;e? artu &yogh;ut inume?</L><L>Artu mid ri&yogh;te ouercume?"</L><L>   "Nay, nay!" sede &thorn;e ni&yogh;tingale,</L><L>" &thorn;u shalt ihere ano&thorn;er tale:</L><L N="545">&yogh;et nis &thorn;os speche ibro&yogh;t to dome. <MILESTONE N="237r.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>Ac bo wel stille, &amp; lust nu to me</L><L>ich shal mid one bare worde</L><L>do &thorn;at &thorn;i speche [wur&thorn;] forwor&thorn;e."</L><L>   "&THORN;at nere noht ri&yogh;t" &thorn;e hule sede,</L><L N="550">"&thorn;u hauest bicloped al so &thorn;u bede, <PB N="50"></L><L>an ich &thorn;e habbe i&yogh;iue ansuare.</L><L>Ac ar we to unker dome fare,</L><L>ich wille speke toward &thorn;e</L><L>al so &thorn;u speke toward me;</L><L N="555">an &thorn;u me ansuare &yogh;if &thorn;u mi&yogh;t.</L><L>Seie me nu, &thorn;u wrecche wi&yogh;t,</L><L>is in &thorn;e eni o&thorn;er note</L><L>bute &thorn;u hauest schille &thorn;rote?</L><L>&THORN;u nart no&yogh;t to non o&thorn;er &thorn;inge,</L><L N="560">bute &thorn;u canst of chateringe:</L><L>vor &thorn;u art lutel an unstrong,</L><L>an nis &thorn;i regel no&thorn;ing long.</L><L>Wat dostu godes among monne?</L><L>Na mo &thorn;e de&thorn; a w[re]cche wranne.</L><L N="565">Of &thorn;e ne cume&thorn; non o&thorn;er god,</L><L>bute &thorn;u gredest suich &thorn;u bo wod:</L><L>an bo &thorn;i piping ouergo,</L><L>ne bo&thorn; on &thorn;e craftes namo.</L><L>Alured sede, &thorn;at was wis:</L><L N="570">(he mi&yogh;te wel, for so&thorn; hit is,)</L><L>"Nis no man for is bare songe</L><L>lof ne w[u]r&thorn; no&yogh;t su&thorn;e longe:</L><L>vor &thorn;at is a forwor&thorn;e man</L><L>&thorn;at bute singe no&yogh;t ne can."</L><L N="575">&THORN;u nart bute on forwor&thorn;e &thorn;ing:</L><L>on &thorn;e nis bute chatering.</L><L>&THORN;u art dim an of fule howe,</L><L>an &thorn;inchest a lutel soti clowe. <PB N="52"></L><L>&THORN;u nart fair, no &thorn;u nart strong, 
<MILESTONE N="237r.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L N="580">ne &thorn;u nart &thorn;icke, ne &thorn;u nart long:   </L><L>&thorn;u hauest imist al of fairhede,</L><L>an lutel is al &thorn;i godede.</L><L>An o&thorn;er &thorn;ing of &thorn;e ich mene,</L><L>&thorn;u nart vair ne &thorn;u nart clene.</L><L N="585">Wane &thorn;u comest to manne ha&yogh;e,</L><L>&thorn;ar &thorn;ornes bo&thorn; &amp; ris idra&yogh;e,</L><L>bi hegge &amp; bi &thorn;icke wode,</L><L>&thorn;ar men go&thorn; oft to hore node,</L><L>&thorn;arto &thorn;u dra&yogh;st, &thorn;arto &thorn;u w[u]nest,</L><L N="590">an o&thorn;er clene stede &thorn;u schunest.</L><L>&THORN;an ich flo ni&yogh;tes after muse,</L><L>I mai &thorn;e uinde ate rum-huse;</L><L>among &thorn;e wode, among &thorn;e netle,</L><L>&thorn;u sittest &amp; singst bihinde &thorn;e setle:</L><L N="595">&thorn;ar me mai &thorn;e ilomest finde,</L><L>&thorn;ar men worpe&thorn; hore bihinde.</L><L>&YOGH;et &thorn;u atuitest me mine mete,</L><L>an seist &thorn;at ich fule wi&yogh;tes ete.</L><L>Ac wat etestu, &thorn;at &thorn;u ne li&yogh;e,</L><L N="600">bute attercoppe &amp; fule ulige,</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 601 through 700</HEAD><L>an wormes, &yogh;if &thorn;u mi&yogh;te finde</L><L>among &thorn;e uolde of harde rinde?</L><L>&YOGH;et ich can do wel gode wike,</L><L>vor ich can loki manne wike:</L><L N="605">an mine wike bo&thorn; wel gode,</L><L>vor ich helpe to manne uode.</L><L>Ich can nimen mus at berne,</L><L>an ek at chirche ine &thorn;e derne:</L><L>vor me is lof to Cristes huse,</L><L N="610">to clansi hit wi&thorn; fule muse,</L><L>ne schal &thorn;ar neure come to</L><L>ful wi&yogh;t, &yogh;if ich hit mai iuo. <PB N="54"></L><L>An &yogh;if me lust one mi skentinge <MILESTONE N="237v.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>to wernen o&thorn;er w[u]nienge,</L><L N="615">ich habbe at wude tron wel grete,</L><L>mit &thorn;icke bo&yogh;e no&thorn;ing blete,</L><L>mid iui grene al bigrowe,</L><L>&thorn;at eure stont iliche iblowe,</L><L>an his hou neuer ne uorlost,</L><L N="620">wan hit sniuw ne wan hit frost.</L><L>&THORN;arin ich habbe god ihold,</L><L>a-winter warm, a -sumere cold.</L><L>Wane min hus stont bri&yogh;t &amp; grene,</L><L>of &thorn;ine nis no&thorn;ing isene.</L><L N="625">&YOGH;et &thorn;u me telst of o&thorn;er &thorn;inge,</L><L>of mine briddes seist gabbinge,</L><L>&thorn;at hore nest nis no&yogh;t clene.</L><L>Hit is fale o&thorn;er wi&yogh;te imene:</L><L>vor hors a-stable &amp; oxe a-stalle</L><L N="630">[d]o&thorn; al &thorn;at hom wule &thorn;ar falle.</L><L>An lutle children in &thorn;e cradele,</L><L>bo&thorn;e chorles an ek a&thorn;ele,</L><L>[d]o&thorn; al &thorn;at in hore &yogh;oe&thorn;e</L><L>&thorn;at hi uorlete&thorn; in hore du&yogh;e&thorn;e.</L><L N="635">Wat! can &thorn;at &yogh;ongling hit bihede?</L><L>&YOGH;if hit misde&thorn;, hit mo[t] nede:</L><L>a uorbisne is of olde i[vu]rne,</L><L>[&thorn;]at node make&thorn; old wif urne. <PB N="56"></L><L>An &yogh;et ich habbe an o&thorn;er andsware:</L><L N="640">wiltu to mine neste uare</L><L>an loki hu hit is idi&yogh;t?</L><L>&YOGH;if &thorn;u art wis lorni &thorn;u [mi&yogh;t]:</L><L>mi nest is hol&yogh; &amp; rum amidde,</L><L>so hit is softest mine bridde.</L><L N="645">Hit is broiden al abute,</L><L>vrom &thorn;e neste uor wi&thorn;ute:</L><L>&thorn;arto hi go[&thorn;] to hore node, <MILESTONE N="237v.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>ac &thorn;at &thorn;u menest ich hom forbode.</L><L>We nime&thorn; &yogh;eme of manne bure,</L><L N="650">an after &thorn;an we make&thorn; ure:</L><L>men habbet, among o&thorn;er i[h]ende,</L><L>a rum-hus at hore bures ende,</L><L>vor &thorn;at hi nelle&thorn; to uor go,</L><L>an mine briddes do&thorn; al so.</L><L N="655">Site nu stille, chaterestre!</L><L>nere &thorn;u neuer ibunde uastre:</L><L>herto ne uindestu neuer andsware.</L><L>Hong up &thorn;in ax! nu &thorn;u mi&yogh;t fare!"</L><L>&THORN;e ni&yogh;tingale at &thorn;isse worde</L><L><L N="660">was wel ne&yogh; ut of rede iwor&thorn;e,</L><L>an &thorn;o&yogh;te &yogh;orne on hire mode</L><L>&yogh;if ho o&yogh;t elles understode,</L><L>&yogh;if ho ku&thorn;e o&yogh;t bute singe,</L><L>&thorn;at mi&yogh;te helpe to o&thorn;er &thorn;inge. <PB N="58"></L><L N="665">Herto ho moste andswere uinde,</L><L>o&thorn;er mid alle bon bihinde:</L><L>an hit is su&thorn;e strong to fi&yogh;te</L><L>a&yogh;en so&thorn; &amp; a&yogh;en ri&yogh;te.</L><L>He mot gon to al mid ginne,</L><L N="670">&thorn;an &thorn;e horte bo&thorn; on [w]inne:</L><L>an &thorn;e man mot on o&thorn;er segge,</L><L>he mot bihemmen &amp; bilegge,</L><L>&yogh;if mu&thorn; wi&thorn;ute mai biwro</L><L>&thorn;at me &thorn;e horte no&yogh;t niso:</L><L N="675">an sone mai a word misreke</L><L>&thorn;ar mu&thorn; shal a&yogh;en horte speke;</L><L>an sone mai a word misstorte</L><L>&thorn;ar mu&thorn; shal speken a&yogh;en horte.</L><L>Ac no&thorn;eles &yogh;ut upe &thorn;on,</L><L N="680">her is to red wo hine kon:</L><L>vor neuer nis wit so kene 
<MILESTONE N="238r.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>so &thorn;ane red him is a-wene.</L><L>&thorn;anne erest kume[&thorn;] his &yogh;ephede</L><L>wone hit is alre-mest on drede:</L><L N="685">for Aluered seide of olde quide,</L><L>an &yogh;ut hit nis of horte islide:</L><L>"Wone &thorn;e bale is alre-hecst,</L><L>&thorn;onne is &thorn;e bote alre-necst"; <PB N="60"></L><L>vor wit west among his sore,</L><L N="690">an for his sore hit is &thorn;e more.</L><L>Vor&thorn;i nis neuere mon redles</L><L>ar his horte bo witles:</L><L>ac &yogh;if &thorn;at he forlost his wit,</L><L>&thorn;onne is his red-purs al to-slit;</L><L N="695">&yogh;if he ne kon his wit atholde,</L><L>ne uint he red in one uolde.</L><L>Vor Alur[e]d seide, &thorn;at wel ku&thorn;e,</L><L>eure he spac mid so&thorn;e mu&thorn;e:</L><L>"Wone &thorn;e bale is alre-hecst,</L><L N="700">&thorn;anne is &thorn;e bote alre-nest."</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 701 through 800</HEAD><L>   &THORN;e ni&yogh;tingale al hire ho&yogh;e</L><L>mid rede hadde wel bito&yogh;e;</L><L>among &thorn;e harde, among &thorn;e to&yogh;te,</L><L>ful wel mid rede hire bi&thorn;o&yogh;te,</L><L N="705">an hadde andsuere gode ifunde</L><L>among al hire harde stunde.</L><L>   "[H]ule, &thorn;u axest me," ho seide,</L><L>"&yogh;if ich kon eni o&thorn;er dede</L><L>bute singen in sume tide,</L><L N="710">an bringe blisse for &amp; wide.</L><L>Wi axestu of craftes mine?</L><L>Betere is min on &thorn;an alle &thorn;ine,</L><L>betere is o song of mine mu&thorn;e</L><L>&thorn;an al &thorn;at eure &thorn;i kun ku&thorn;e:</L><L N="715">an lust, ich telle &thorn;e wareuore. 
<MILESTONE N="238r.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>Wostu to wan man was ibore?</L><L>To &thorn;are blisse of houene-riche,</L><L>&thorn;ar euer is song &amp; mur&yogh;&thorn;e iliche: <PB N="62"></L><L>&thorn;ider funde&thorn; eurich man</L><L N="720">&thorn;at eni &thorn;ing of gode kan.</L><L>Vor&thorn;i me sing&thorn; in holi-chirche,</L><L>an clerkes ginne&thorn; songes wirche,</L><L>&thorn;at man i&thorn;enche bi &thorn;e songe</L><L>wider he shal, &amp; &thorn;ar bon longe:</L><L N="725">&thorn;at he &thorn;e mur&yogh;&thorn;e ne uor&yogh;ete,</L><L>ac &thorn;arof &thorn;enche &amp; bi&yogh;ete,</L><L>an nime &yogh;eme of chirche steuene,</L><L>hu murie is &thorn;e blisse of houene.</L><L>Clerkes, munekes, &amp; kanunes,</L><L N="730">&thorn;ar bo&thorn; &thorn;os gode wicke-tunes,</L><L>arise&thorn; up to midel-ni&yogh;te,</L><L>an singe&thorn; of &thorn;e houene-li&yogh;te:</L><L>an prostes upe londe singe&thorn;,</L><L>wane &thorn;e li&yogh;t of daie springe&thorn;.</L><L N="735">An ich hom helpe wat I mai,</L><L>ich singe mid hom ni&yogh;t &amp; dai,</L><L>an ho bo&thorn; alle for me &thorn;e gladdere,</L><L>an to &thorn;e songe bo&thorn; &thorn;e raddere.</L><L>Ich warni men to hore gode,</L><L N="740">&thorn;at hi bon bli&thorn;e on hore mode,</L><L>an bidde &thorn;at hi moten iseche</L><L>&thorn;an ilke song &thorn;at euer is eche.</L><L>Nu &thorn;u mi&yogh;t, hule, sitte &amp; clinge:</L><L>her-among nis no chateringe:</L><L N="745">ich graunti &thorn;at [w]e go to dome</L><L>tofore &thorn;e [sulfe Pope] of Rome. <PB N="64"></L><L>Ac abid &yogh;ete, no&thorn;eles,</L><L>&thorn;u shalt ihere an o&thorn;er [h]es;</L><L>ne shaltu, for Engelonde, 
<MILESTONE N="238v.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L N="750">at &thorn;isse worde me atstonde.     </L><L>Wi atuitestu me mine unstreng&thorn;e,</L><L>an mine ungrete &amp; mine unleng&thorn;e,</L><L>an seist &thorn;at ich nam no&yogh;t strong,</L><L>vor ich nam no&thorn;er gret ne long?</L><L N="755">Ac &thorn;u nost neuer wat &thorn;u menst,</L><L>bute lese wordes &thorn;u me lenst:</L><L>for ich kan craft &amp; ich kan liste,</L><L>an [&thorn;]areuore ich am &thorn;us &thorn;riste.</L><L>Ich kan wit &amp; song man[t]eine,</L><L N="760">ne triste ich to non o&thorn;er maine:</L><L>vor so&thorn; hit is &thorn;at seide Alured:</L><L>"Ne mai no streng&thorn;e a&yogh;en red." <PB N="66"></L><L>Oft spet wel a lute liste,</L><L>&thorn;ar muche streng&thorn;e sholde miste;</L><L N="765">mid lutle streng&thorn;e, &thorn;ur&yogh; ginne,</L><L>castel &amp; bur&yogh; me mai iwinne.</L><L>Mid liste me mai walle[s] felle,</L><L>an worpe of horsse kni&yogh;tes snelle.</L><L>Vuel streng&thorn;e is lutel wur&thorn;,</L><L N="770"> *     *     *     *     *</L><L> *     *     *     *     *</L><L>ac wisdom naue&thorn; non euening.</L><L>An hors is strengur &thorn;an a mon;</L><L>ac for hit non iwit ne kon,</L><L N="775">hit ber&thorn; on rugge grete semes,</L><L>an dra&yogh;&thorn; biuore grete temes, <PB N="68"></L><L>an &thorn;ole&thorn; bo&thorn;e &yogh;erd &amp; spure,</L><L>an stont iteid at mulne dure.</L><L>An hit de&thorn; &thorn;at mon hit hot:</L><L N="780">an for &thorn;an &thorn;at hit no wit not,</L><L>ne mai his stren&thorn;e hit ishilde</L><L>&thorn;at hit nabu&yogh;&thorn; &thorn;e lutle childe.</L><L>Mon de&thorn;, mid streng&thorn;e &amp; mid witte,</L><L>&thorn;at o&thorn;er &thorn;ing nis non his fitte.</L><L N="785">&THORN;e&yogh; alle streng&thorn;e at one were, 
<MILESTONE N="238v.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>monnes wit &yogh;et more were;</L><L>vor &thorn;e mon mid his crafte,</L><L>ouerkume&thorn; al or&thorn;liche shafte.</L><L>Al so ich do mid mine one songe</L><L N="790">bet &thorn;an &thorn;u al &thorn;e &yogh;er longe:</L><L>vor mine crafte men me luuie&thorn;,</L><L>vor &thorn;ine streng&thorn;e men &thorn;e shunie&thorn;.</L><L>Telstu bi me &thorn;e wurs for &thorn;an</L><L>&thorn;at ich bute anne craft ne kan?</L><L N="795">&YOGH;if tueie men go&thorn; to wraslinge,</L><L>an ei&thorn;er o&thorn;er faste &thorn;ringe,</L><L>an &thorn;e on can swenges su&thorn;e fele,</L><L>an kan his wrenches wel forhele,</L><L>an &thorn;e o&thorn;er ne can sweng but anne,</L><L N="800">an &thorn;e is god wi&thorn; eche manne,</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 801 through 900</HEAD><L>an mid &thorn;on one lei&thorn; to grunde</L><L>anne after o&thorn;er a lutle stunde,</L><L>[w]at &thorn;arf he recche of a mo swenge,</L><L>&thorn;one &thorn;e on him is swo genge? <PB N="70"></L><L N="805">&THORN;[u] seist &thorn;at &thorn;u canst fele wike,</L><L>ac euer ich am &thorn;in unilike.</L><L>Do &thorn;ine craftes alle togadere,</L><L>&yogh;et is min on horte betere.</L><L>Oft &thorn;an hundes foxes driue&thorn;,</L><L N="810">&thorn;e kat ful wel him sulue liue&thorn;,</L><L>&thorn;e&yogh; he ne kunne wrench bute anne.</L><L>&THORN;e fo[x] so godne ne can nanne,</L><L>&thorn;e[&yogh;] he kunne so uele wrenche,</L><L>&thorn;at he wen&thorn; eche hunde atprenche.</L><L N="815">Vor he can pa&thorn;es ri&yogh;te &amp; wo&yogh;e,</L><L>an he kan hongi bi &thorn;e bo&yogh;e,</L><L>an so forlost &thorn;e hund his fore,</L><L>an turn&thorn; a&yogh;en eft to &thorn;an more.</L><L>&THORN;e uox kan crope bi &thorn;e heie, 
<MILESTONE N="239r.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L N="820">an turne ut from his forme weie,   </L><L>an eft sone kume &thorn;arto:</L><L>&thorn;onne is &thorn;e hundes smel fordo:</L><L>he not, &thorn;ur[&yogh;] &thorn;e imeinde smak,</L><L>we&thorn;er he shal auor&thorn; &thorn;e abak.</L><L N="825">&YOGH;if &thorn;e uox mist of al &thorn;is dwole,</L><L>at &thorn;an ende he crop&thorn; to hole: <PB N="72"></L><L>ac na&thorn;eles mid alle his wrenche,</L><L>ne kan he hine so bi&thorn;enche,</L><L>&thorn;e&yogh; he bo &yogh;ep an su&thorn;e snel,</L><L N="830">&thorn;at he ne lost his rede uel.</L><L>&THORN;e cat ne kan wrench bute anne</L><L>no&thorn;er bi dune ne bi uenne:</L><L>bute he kan climbe su&thorn;e wel,</L><L>&thorn;armid he were&thorn; his greie uel.</L><L N="835">Al so ich segge bi mi solue,</L><L>betere is min on &thorn;an &thorn;ine twelue."</L><L>   "Abid! abid!" &thorn;e ule seide,</L><L>"&thorn;u gest al to mid swikelede:</L><L>alle &thorn;ine wordes &thorn;u bileist</L><L N="840">&thorn;at hit &thorn;inc&thorn; so&thorn; al &thorn;at &thorn;u seist;</L><L>alle &thorn;ine wordes bo&thorn; isliked,</L><L>an so bisemed an biliked,</L><L>&thorn;at alle &thorn;o &thorn;at hi auo&thorn;,</L><L>hi wene&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;u segge so&thorn;.</L><L N="845">Abid! abid! me shal &thorn;e &yogh;ene.</L><L>[N]u hit shal w[u]r&thorn;e wel isene</L><L>&thorn;at &thorn;u hauest muchel ilo&yogh;e,</L><L>wone &thorn;i lesing bo&thorn; unwro&yogh;e.</L><L>&THORN;u seist &thorn;at &thorn;u singist mankunne,</L><L N="850">&amp; techest hom &thorn;at hi fundie&thorn; honne</L><L>vp to &thorn;e songe &thorn;at eure ilest:</L><L>ac hit is alre w[u]nder mest,</L><L>&thorn;at &thorn;u darst li&yogh;e so opeliche. 
<MILESTONE N="239r.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>Wenest &thorn;u hi bringe so li&yogh;tliche</L><L N="855">to Godes riche al singin[d]e?</L><L>Nai! nai! hi shulle wel auinde <PB N="74"></L><L>&thorn;at hi mid longe wope mote</L><L>of hore sunnen bidde bote,</L><L>ar hi mote euer kume &thorn;are.</L><L N="860">Ich rede &thorn;i &thorn;at men bo &yogh;are,</L><L>an more wepe &thorn;ane singe,</L><L>&thorn;at funde&thorn; to &thorn;an houen-kinge:</L><L>vor nis no man witute sunne.</L><L>Vor&thorn;i he mot, ar he wende honne,</L><L N="865">mid teres an mid wope bete,</L><L>&thorn;at him bo sur &thorn;at er was swete.</L><L>&THORN;arto ich helpe, God hit wot!</L><L>Ne singe i[c]h hom no foliot:</L><L>for al m[i] song is of longinge,</L><L N="870">an imend sumdel mid woninge,</L><L>&thorn;at mon bi me hine bi&thorn;enche</L><L>&thorn;at he gro[ni] for his unwrenche:</L><L>mid mine songe ich hine pulte,</L><L>&thorn;at he groni for his gulte.</L><L N="875">&YOGH;if &thorn;u gest herof to disputinge,</L><L>ich wepe bet &thorn;ane &thorn;u singe:</L><L>&yogh;if ri&yogh;t go&thorn; for&thorn;, &amp; abak wrong,</L><L>betere is mi wop &thorn;ane &thorn;i song.</L><L>&THORN;e&yogh; sume men bo  &thorn;ur&yogh;ut gode,</L><L N="880">an &thorn;ur&yogh;ut clene on hore mode,</L><L>ho[m] longe&thorn; honne no&thorn;eles.</L><L>&THORN;at bo&thorn; her, [w]o is hom &thorn;es:</L><L>vor &thorn;e&yogh; hi bon hom solue ibor&yogh;e,</L><L>hi ne so&thorn; her nowi&yogh;t bote sorwe.</L><L N="885">Vor o&thorn;er men hi wepe&thorn; sore,</L><L>an for hom bidde&thorn; Cristes ore. <PB N="76"></L><L>Ich helpe monne on ei&thorn;er halue, 
<MILESTONE N="239v.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>mi mu&thorn; haue&thorn; tweire kunne salue :</L><L>&thorn;an gode ich fulste to longinge,</L><L N="890">vor &thorn;an hi[m] longe&thorn;, ich him singe:</L><L>an &thorn;an sunfulle ich helpe alswo,</L><L>vor ich him teche &thorn;are is wo.</L><L>&YOGH;et ich &thorn;e &yogh;ene in o&thorn;er wise:</L><L>vor &thorn;ane &thorn;u sittest on &thorn;ine rise,</L><L N="895">&thorn;u dra&yogh;st men to fleses luste,</L><L>&thorn;at w[u]lle&thorn; &thorn;ine songes luste.</L><L>Al &thorn;u forlost &thorn;e mur&yogh;&thorn;e of houene,</L><L>for &thorn;arto neuestu none steuene :</L><L>al &thorn;at &thorn;u singst is of golnesse,</L><L N="900">for nis on &thorn;e non holinesse,</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 901 through 1000</HEAD><L>ne wene[&thorn;] na man for &thorn;i pipinge</L><L>&thorn;at eni preost in chir[ch]e singe.</L><L>&YOGH;et I &thorn;e wulle an o[&thorn;]er segge,</L><L>&yogh;if &thorn;u hit const ariht bilegge:</L><L N="905">[w]i nultu singe an o[&thorn;]er &thorn;eode,</L><L>&thorn;ar hit is muchele more neode?</L><L>&THORN;u neauer ne singst in Irlonde,</L><L>ne &thorn;u ne cumest no&yogh;t in Scotlonde.</L><L>Hwi nultu fare to Noreweie,</L><L N="910">an singin men of Galeweie? <PB N="78"></L><L>&THORN;ar beo&eth; men &thorn;at lutel kunne</L><L>of songe &thorn;at is bineo&eth; &thorn;e sunne.</L><L>Wi nultu &thorn;are preoste singe,</L><L>an teche of &thorn;ire writelinge,</L><L N="915"> an wisi hom mid &thorn;ire steuene</L><L>hu engeles singe&eth; ine heouene?</L><L>&THORN;u farest so do&eth; an ydel wel</L><L>&thorn;at springe&thorn; bi burue &thorn;a[t] is snel,</L><L>an let fordrue &thorn;e dune,</L><L N="920">&amp; flo[&thorn;] on idel &thorn;ar adune.</L><L>Ac ich fare bo&thorn;e nor&thorn; &amp; s[u]&thorn;: 
<MILESTONE N="239v.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>in eauereuch londe ich am cuu&thorn;:</L><L>east &amp; west, feor &amp; neor,</L><L>I do wel faire mi meoster,</L><L N="925">an warni men mid mine bere,</L><L>&thorn;at &thorn;i dweole-song heo ne forlere.</L><L>Ich wisse men mid min[e] songe,</L><L>&thorn;at hi ne sunegi nowiht longe :</L><L>I bidde hom &thorn;at heo iswike,</L><L N="930">&thorn;at [heo] heom seolue ne biswike:</L><L>for betere is &thorn;at heo wepen here,</L><L>&thorn;an elles hwar [beon] deoulene fere."</L><L>   &THORN;e ni&yogh;tingale was igr[amed]</L><L>an ek heo was sum del of[s]chamed,</L><L N="935">for &thorn;e hule hire atwiten hadde</L><L>in hwucche stude he sat an gradde,</L><L>bihinde &thorn;e bure, among &thorn;e wede,</L><L>&thorn;ar men go&eth; to here neode: <PB N="80"></L><L>an sat sum-del, &amp; heo bi&thorn;ohte,</L><L N="940">an wiste wel on hire &thorn;ohte</L><L>&thorn;e wra&thorn;&thorn;e binime&thorn; monnes red.</L><L>For hit seide &thorn;e king Alfred:</L><L>"Sel[d]e ende&eth; wel &thorn;e lo&thorn;e,</L><L>an selde plaide&eth; wel &thorn;e wro&thorn;e."</L><L N="945">For wra&thorn;&thorn;e mein&thorn; &thorn;e horte blod</L><L>&thorn;at hit flowe&thorn; so wilde flod,</L><L>an al &thorn;e heorte ouerge&thorn;,</L><L>&thorn;at heo naue&thorn; no &thorn;ing bute bre&thorn;,</L><L>an so forleost al hire liht,</L><L N="950">&thorn;at heo ni si&thorn; so&thorn; ne riht.</L><L>&THORN;e ni&yogh;tingale hi understod,</L><L>an ouergan lette hire mod:</L><L>he mihte bet speken a-sele</L><L>&thorn;an mid wra&thorn;&thorn;e wordes deale.</L><L N="955">   "[H]ule," heo seide "lust nu hider: 
<MILESTONE N="240r.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>&thorn;u schalt falle, &thorn;e wei is slider.</L><L>&THORN;u seist ich fleo bihinde bure:</L><L>hit is riht, &thorn;e bur is ure:</L><L>&thorn;ar lauerd ligge&thorn; &amp; lauedi,</L><L N="960">ich schal heom singe &amp; sitte bi.</L><L>Wenstu &thorn;at uise men forlete,</L><L>for fule venne, &thorn;e ri&yogh;tte strete ?</L><L>ne sunne &thorn;e later shine,</L><L>&thorn;e&yogh; hit bo ful ine nest[e] &thorn;ine?</L><L N="965">Sholde ich, for one hole brede,</L><L>forlete mine ri&yogh;te stede, <PB N="82"></L><L>&thorn;at ich ne singe bi &thorn;e bedde,</L><L>&thorn;ar louerd haue&thorn; his loue ibedde?</L><L>Hit is mi ri&yogh;t, hit is mi la&yogh;e,</L><L N="970">&thorn;a[t] to &thorn;e he[x]st ich me dra&yogh;e.</L><L>Ac &yogh;et &thorn;u &yogh;elpst of &thorn;ine songe,</L><L>&thorn;at &thorn;u canst &yogh;olle wro&thorn;e &amp; stronge,</L><L>an seist &thorn;u uisest mankunne,</L><L>&thorn;at hi biwepen hore sunne.</L><L N="975">Solde euch mon wonie &amp; grede</L><L>ri&yogh;t suich hi weren unlede,</L><L>solde hi &yogh;ollen al so &thorn;u dest,</L><L>hi mi&yogh;te oferen here brost.</L><L>Man schal bo stille &amp; no&yogh;t grede;</L><L N="980">he mot biwepe his misdede:</L><L>ac &thorn;ar is Cristes heriinge,</L><L>&thorn;ar me shal grede &amp; lude singe.</L><L>Nis no&thorn;er to lud ne to long,</L><L>at ri&yogh;te time, chirche-song.</L><L N="985">&THORN;u &yogh;olst &amp; wones[t], &amp; ich singe:</L><L>&thorn;i steuene is wop, &amp; min skentinge.</L><L>Euer mote &thorn;u &yogh;olle &amp; wepen</L><L>&thorn;at &thorn;u &thorn;i lif mote forleten!</L><L>an &yogh;ollen mote &thorn;u so he&yogh;e <MILESTONE N="240r.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L N="990">&thorn;at ut berste bo &thorn;in e&yogh;e!       </L><L>We&thorn;er is betere of twe[n]e twom,</L><L>&thorn;at mon bo bli&thorn;e o&thorn;er grom ? <PB N="84"></L><L>So bo hit euer in unker si&thorn;e,</L><L>&thorn;at &thorn;u bo sori &amp; ich bli&thorn;e.</L><L N="995">&YOGH;ut &thorn;u aisheist wi ich ne fare</L><L>into o&thorn;er londe &amp; singe &thorn;are?</L><L>No! wat sholde ich among hom do,</L><L>&thorn;ar neuer blisse ne com to?</L><L>&THORN;at lond nis god, ne hit nis este,</L><L N="1000">ac wildernisse hit is &amp; weste:</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 1001 through 1100</HEAD><L>knarres &amp; cludes houen[e]-tinge,</L><L>snou &amp; ha&yogh;el hom is genge.</L><L>&THORN;at lond is grislich &amp; unuele,</L><L>&thorn;e men bo&thorn; wilde &amp; unisele,</L><L N="1005">hi nabbe&thorn; no&thorn;er gri&thorn; ne sibbe:</L><L>hi ne recche&thorn; hu hi libbe.</L><L>Hi ete&thorn; fihs an flehs unsode,</L><L>suich wulues hit hadde tobrode:</L><L>hi drinke&thorn; milc &amp; wei &thorn;arto,</L><L N="1010"> hi nute elles &thorn;at hi do: <PB N="86"></L><L>hi nabbe&thorn; no&thorn;[er] win ne bor,</L><L>ac libbe&thorn; al so wilde dor:</L><L>hi go&thorn; biti&yogh;t mid ru&yogh;e uelle,</L><L>ri&yogh;t suich hi comen ut of helle.</L><L N="1015">&THORN;e&yogh; eni god man to hom come,</L><L>so wile dude sum from Rome,</L><L>for hom to lere gode &thorn;ewes,</L><L>an for to leten hore un&thorn;ewes,</L><L>he mi&yogh;te bet sitte stille,</L><L N="1020">vor al his wile he sholde spille:</L><L>he mi&yogh;te bet teche ane bore</L><L>to we&yogh;e bo&thorn;e sheld &amp; spere,</L><L>&thorn;an me &thorn;at wilde folc ibringe 
<MILESTONE N="240v.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>&thorn;at hi [me] wolde ihere singe.</L><L N="1025">Wat sol[d]ich &thorn;ar mid mine songe?</L><L>ne sunge ich hom neuer so longe,</L><L>mi song were ispild ech del:</L><L>for hom ne mai halter ne bridel</L><L>bringe vrom hore w[o]de wise,</L><L N="1030">ne mon mid stele ne mid i[s]e. <PB N="88"></L><L>Ac war lon[d] is bo&thorn;e este &amp; god,</L><L>an &thorn;ar men habbe&thorn; milde mod,</L><L>ich noti mid hom mine &thorn;rote,</L><L>vor ich mai do &thorn;ar gode note:</L><L N="1035">an bringe hom loue ti&thorn;inge,</L><L>vor ich of chirche-songe singe.</L><L>Hit was iseid in olde la&yogh;e,</L><L>an &yogh;et ilast &thorn;ilke so&thorn;-sa&yogh;e,</L><L>&thorn;at man shal erien an sowe,</L><L N="1040">&thorn;ar he wen&thorn; after sum god mowe:</L><L>for he is wod &thorn;at sowe&thorn; his sed</L><L>&thorn;ar neuer gras ne sprin&thorn; ne bled."</L><L>   &THORN;e hule was wro&thorn;, to cheste rad,</L><L>mid &thorn;isse worde hire e&yogh;en abrad:</L><L N="1045">"&THORN;u seist &thorn;u witest manne bures,</L><L>&thorn;ar leues bo&thorn; &amp; faire flores,</L><L>&thorn;ar two iloue in one bedde</L><L>ligge&thorn; biclop[t] &amp; wel bihedde.</L><L>Enes &thorn;u sunge, ic wo[t] wel ware,</L><L N="1050">bi one bure, &amp; woldest lere</L><L>&thorn;e lefdi to an uuel luue,</L><L>an sunge bo&thorn;e lo&yogh;e &amp; buue, <PB N="90"></L><L>an lerdest hi to don shome</L><L>an vnri&yogh;t of hire licome.</L><L N="1055">&THORN;e louerd &thorn;at sone under&yogh;at,</L><L>liim &amp; grine [&amp;]  wel eiwat,</L><L>sette &amp; le[i]de &thorn;e for to lacche.</L><L>&THORN;u come sone to &thorn;an hacche,</L><L>&thorn;u were inume in one grine,</L><L N="1060">al hit abo&yogh;te &thorn;ine shine:</L><L>&thorn;u naddest non o&thorn;er dom ne la&yogh;e,</L><L>bute mid wilde horse were todra&yogh;e.</L><L>Vonde &yogh;if &thorn;u mi&yogh;t eft misrede,</L><L>wa&thorn;er &thorn;u wult, wif &thorn;e maide:</L><L N="1065">&thorn;i song mai bo so longe genge</L><L>&thorn;at &thorn;u shalt wippen on a sprenge."</L><L>   &THORN;e ni&yogh;tingale at &thorn;isse worde,</L><L>mid sworde an mid speres orde,</L><L>&yogh;if ho mon were, wolde fi&yogh;te:</L><L N="1070">ac &thorn;o ho bet do ne mi&yogh;te,</L><L>ho ua&yogh;t mid hire wise tunge.</L><L>"Wel fi&yogh;t &thorn;at wel spec&thorn;," sei&thorn; in &thorn;e songe.</L><L>Of hire tunge ho nom red:</L><L>"Wel fi&yogh;t &thorn;at wel spec&thorn;" seide Alured.</L><L N="1075">   "Wat! seistu &thorn;is for mine shome?</L><L>&thorn;e louerd hadde herof grame.</L><L>He was so gelus of his wiue,</L><L>&thorn;at he ne mi&yogh;te for his liue</L><L>iso &thorn;at man wi&thorn; hire speke,</L><L N="1080">&thorn;at his horte nolde breke.</L><L>He hire bileck in one bure,</L><L>&thorn;at hire was bo&thorn;e stronge &amp; sure: <PB N="92"></L><L>ich hadde of hire milse an ore,</L><L>an sori was for hire sore,</L><L N="1085">an skente hi mid mine songe</L><L>al &thorn;at ich mi&yogh;te, ra&thorn;e an longe.</L><L>Vor&thorn;an &thorn;e kni&yogh;t was wi&thorn; me wro&thorn;,</L><L>vor ri&yogh;te ni&thorn;e ich was him lo&thorn;:</L><L>he dude me his o&yogh;ene shome,</L><L N="1090">ac al him turnde it to grome.</L><L>&THORN;at underyat &thorn;e king Henri: 
<MILESTONE N="241r.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>Jesus his soule do merci!</L><L>He let forbonne &thorn;ene kni&yogh;t,</L><L>&thorn;at hadde idon so muchel unri&yogh;t</L><L N="1095">ine so gode kinges londe;</L><L>vor ri&yogh;te ni&thorn;e &amp; for fule onde</L><L>let &thorn;ane lutle fu&yogh;el nime</L><L>an him fordeme lif an lime.</L><L>Hit was w[u]r&thorn;sipe al mine kunne;</L><L N="1100">for&thorn;on &thorn;e kni&yogh;t forles his wunne,</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 1101 through 1200</HEAD><L>an &yogh;af for me an hundred punde:</L><L>an mine briddes seten isunde, <PB N="94"></L><L>an hadde so&thorn;&thorn;e blisse &amp; hi&yogh;te,</L><L>an were bli&thorn;e, &amp; wel mi&yogh;te.</L><L N="1105">Vor&thorn;on ich was so wel awreke,</L><L>euer eft ich dar[r] &thorn;e bet speke:</L><L>vor hit bitidde ene swo,</L><L>ich am &thorn;e bli&thorn;ur euer mo.</L><L>Nu ich mai singe war ich wulle,</L><L N="1110">ne dar me neuer eft mon agrulle.</L><L>Ac &thorn;u, eremi[n]g! &thorn;u wrecche gost!</L><L>&thorn;u ne canst finde, ne &thorn;u nost,</L><L>an hol&yogh; stok &thorn;ar &thorn;u &thorn;e mi&yogh;t hude,</L><L>&thorn;at me ne twenge&thorn; &thorn;ine hude.</L><L N="1115">Vor children, gromes, heme &amp; hine,</L><L>hi &thorn;enche&thorn; alle of &thorn;ire pine:</L><L>&yogh;if hi mu&yogh;e iso &thorn;e sitte,</L><L>stones hi do&thorn; in hore slitte,</L><L>an &thorn;e totorue[&thorn;] &amp; tohene&thorn;,</L><L N="1120">an &thorn;ine fule bon toshene&thorn;.</L><L>&YOGH;if &thorn;u art iworpe o&thorn;er ishote,</L><L>&thorn;anne &thorn;u mi&yogh;t erest to note.</L><L>Vor me &thorn;e ho&thorn; in one rodde,</L><L>an &thorn;u, mid &thorn;ine fule codde,</L><L N="1125">an mid &thorn;ine ateliche s[w]ore, 
<MILESTONE N="241r.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>biwerest manne corn urom dore. <PB N="96"></L><L>Nis no&thorn;er no&yogh;t, &thorn;i lif ne &thorn;i blod:</L><L>ac &thorn;u art sh[e]ueles su&thorn;e god.</L><L>&THORN;ar nowe sedes bo&thorn;e isowe,</L><L N="1130">pinnuc, golfinc, rok, ne crowe</L><L>ne dar &thorn;ar neuer cumen ihende,</L><L>&yogh;if &thorn;i buc honge&thorn; at &thorn;an ende.</L><L>&THORN;ar tron shulle a&yogh;ere blowe,</L><L>an &yogh;unge sedes springe &amp; growe,</L><L N="1135">ne dar no fu&yogh;el &thorn;arto uonge,</L><L>&yogh;if &thorn;u art &thorn;arouer ihonge.</L><L>&THORN;i lif is eure lu&thorn;er &amp; qued,</L><L>&thorn;u nar[t] no&yogh;t bute ded.</L><L>Nu &thorn;u mi&yogh;t wite sikerliche</L><L N="1140">&thorn;at &thorn;ine leches bo&thorn; grisliche</L><L>&thorn;e wile &thorn;u art on lifda&yogh;e:</L><L>vor wane &thorn;u hongest isla&yogh;e,</L><L>&yogh;ut hi bo&thorn; of &thorn;e ofdradde,</L><L>&thorn;e fu&yogh;eles &thorn;at &thorn;e er bigradde.</L><L N="1145">Mid ri&yogh;te men bo&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;e wro&thorn;e,</L><L>for &thorn;u singist euer of hore lo&thorn;e:</L><L>al &thorn;at &thorn;u singst, ra&thorn;e o&thorn;er late,</L><L>hit is euer of manne unwate:</L><L>wane &thorn;u hauest ani&yogh;t igrad,</L><L N="1150">men bo&thorn; of &thorn;e wel sore ofdrad. <PB N="98"></L><L>&THORN;u singst &thorn;ar sum man shal be ded:</L><L>euer &thorn;u bodest sumne qued.</L><L>&THORN;u singst a&yogh;en ei&yogh;te lure,</L><L>o&thorn;er of summe frondes rure :</L><L N="1155">o&thorn;er &thorn;u bodes[t] huses brune,</L><L>o&thorn;er ferde of manne, o&thorn;er &thorn;oues rune;</L><L>o&thorn;er &thorn;u bodest cualm of oreue,</L><L>o&thorn;er &thorn;at londfolc wur&thorn; idorue,</L><L>o&thorn;er &thorn;at wif lost hire make; 
<MILESTONE N="241v.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L N="1160">o&thorn;er &thorn;u bodest cheste an sake.   </L><L>Euer &thorn;u singist of manne hareme,</L><L>&thorn;ur&yogh; &thorn;e hi bo&thorn; sori &amp; areme.</L><L>&thorn;u ne singst neuer one si&thorn;e,</L><L>&thorn;at hit nis for sum unsi&thorn;e.</L><L N="1165">Heruore hit is &thorn;at me &thorn;e shune&thorn;,</L><L>an &thorn;e totorue&thorn; &amp; tobune&thorn;</L><L>mid staue, &amp; stoone, &amp; turf, &amp; clute,</L><L>&thorn;at &thorn;u ne mi&yogh;t nowar atrute.</L><L>Dahet euer suich budel in tune</L><L N="1170">&thorn;at euer bode&thorn; unwreste rune,</L><L>an euer bringe&thorn; vuele ti&thorn;inge,</L><L>an &thorn;at euer spec&thorn; of vuele &thorn;inge!</L><L>God Almi&yogh;ti w[u]r&thorn;e him wro&thorn;,</L><L>an al &thorn;at werie&thorn; linnene clo&thorn;!"</L><L N="1175">   &THORN;e hule ne abo[d] no&yogh;t swi&thorn;[e] longe,</L><L>ah &yogh;ef ondsware starke &amp; stronge:</L><L>" Wat," qua&thorn; ho, " hartu ihoded ?</L><L>o&thorn;er &thorn;u kursest al unihoded ? <PB N="100"></L><L>For prestes wike ich wat &thorn;u dest.</L><L N="1180">Ich not &yogh;ef &thorn;u were &yogh;aure prest:</L><L>ich not &yogh;ef &thorn;u canst masse singe:</L><L>inoh &thorn;u canst of mansinge.</L><L>Ah hit is for &thorn;ine alde ni&thorn;e,</L><L>&thorn;at &thorn;u me akursedest o&thorn;er si&thorn;e:</L><L N="1185">ah &thorn;arto is lihtlich ondsware;</L><L>"Drah to &thorn;e!" cwa&thorn; &thorn;e cartare.</L><L>Wi attwitestu me mine insihte,</L><L>an min iwit &amp; mine mi&yogh;te?</L><L>For ich am witi ful iwis,</L><L N="1190">an wo[t] al &thorn;at to kumen is:</L><L>ich wot of hunger, of hergonge:</L><L>ich wot &yogh;ef men schule libbe longe:</L><L>ich wat &yogh;ef wif lus[t] hire make: 
<MILESTONE N="241v.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>ich wat &thorn;ar schal beo ni&thorn; &amp; wrake;</L><L N="1195">ich wot hwo schal beon [an]honge,</L><L>o&thorn;er elles fulne de&thorn; afonge.</L><L>&YOGH;ef men habbe&thorn; bataile inume,</L><L>ich wat hwa&thorn;er schal beon ouerkume :</L><L>ich wat &yogh;if cwalm scal comen on orfe,</L><L N="1200">an &yogh;if dor schul ligge [a]storue; <PB N="102"></L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 1201 through 1300</HEAD><L>ich wot &yogh;ef treon schule blowe:</L><L>ich wat &yogh;ef cornes schule growe :</L><L>ich wot &yogh;ef huses schule berne:</L><L>ich wot &yogh;ef men schule eorne o&thorn;er erne:</L><L N="1205">ich wot &yogh;ef sea schal schipes drenche:</L><L>ich wot &yogh;ef snuw[e] schal uuele clenche.</L><L>An &yogh;et ich con muchel more:</L><L>ich con inoh in bokes lore,</L><L>an eke ich can of &thorn;e Goddspelle</L><L N="1210">more &thorn;an ich nule &thorn;e telle:</L><L>for ich at chirche come ilome,</L><L>an muche leorni of wisdome :</L><L>ich wat al of &thorn;e tacninge,</L><L>an of o&thorn;er feole &thorn;inge.</L><L N="1215">&YOGH;ef eni mon schal rem abide,</L><L>al ich hit wot ear hit itide. <PB N="104"></L><L>Ofte, for mine muchele iwitte,</L><L>wel sori-mod &amp; w[ro]&thorn; ich sitte :</L><L>wan ich iseo &thorn;at sum wrechede</L><L N="1220">is manne neh, innoh ich grede:</L><L>ich bidde &thorn;at men beon iwar[r]e,</L><L>an habbe gode reades &yogh;ar[r]e.</L><L>For Alfred seide a wis word,</L><L>euch mon hit schulde legge on hord:</L><L N="1225">"&YOGH;ef &thorn;u isihst [er] he beo icume,</L><L>his str[e]nc&thorn;e is him wel neh binume."</L><L>An grete duntes beo&thorn; &thorn;e lasse, 
<MILESTONE N="242r.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>&yogh;ef me ikep&thorn; mid iwarnesse,</L><L>an [flo] schal toward mis&yogh;enge,</L><L N="1230">&yogh;ef &thorn;u isihst hu fleo of strenge;</L><L>for &thorn;u mi&yogh;t blenche wel &amp; fleo,</L><L>&yogh;if &thorn;u isihst heo to &thorn;e teo.</L><L>&THORN;at eni man beo falle in [e]dwite,</L><L>wi schal he me his sor atwite?</L><L N="1235">&THORN;ah ich iseo his harm biuore,</L><L>ne come&thorn; hit no&yogh;t of me &thorn;aru[o]re.</L><L>&THORN;ah &thorn;u iseo &thorn;at sum blind mon,</L><L>&thorn;at nanne rihtne wei ne con,</L><L>to &thorn;are diche his dweole fulie[&thorn;],</L><L N="1240">an falle&thorn;, and &thorn;arone sulie[&thorn;], <PB N="106"></L><L>wenest &thorn;u, &thorn;ah ich al iseo,</L><L>&thorn;at hit for me &thorn;e ra&thorn;ere beo?</L><L>Al swo hit fare&thorn; bi mine witte:</L><L>hwanne ich on mine bowe sitte,</L><L N="1245">ich wot &amp; iseo swi&thorn;e brihte</L><L>an summe men kume[&amp;] harm &thorn;arrihte.</L><L>Schal he, &thorn;at &thorn;erof no&thorn;ing not,</L><L>hit wite me for ich hit wot?</L><L>Schal he his mishap wite me,</L><L N="1250">for ich am wisure &thorn;ane he?</L><L>Hwanne ich iseo &thorn;at sum wrechede</L><L>is manne neh, inoh ich grede,</L><L>an bidde inoh &thorn;at hi heom schilde,</L><L>for toward heom is [harm unmilde].</L><L N="1255">Ah &thorn;ah ich grede lude an stille,</L><L>al hit itid &thorn;ur[h] Godes wille.</L><L>Hwi wulle&thorn; men of me hi mene,</L><L>&thorn;ah ich mid so&thorn;e heo awene?</L><L>&THORN;ah ich hi warni al &thorn;at &yogh;er,</L><L N="1260">nis heom &thorn;erfore harem no &thorn;e ner: 
<MILESTONE N="242r.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>ah ich heom singe for ich wolde</L><L>&thorn;at hi wel understonde schulde</L><L>&thorn;at sum unsel&thorn;e heom is ihende,</L><L>hwan ich min huing to heom sende.</L><L N="1265">Naue&thorn; no man none sikerhede</L><L>&thorn;at he ne mai wene &amp; adrede</L><L>&thorn;at sum unhwate ne[h] him beo,</L><L>&thorn;ah he ne conne hit iseo.</L><L>For&thorn;i seide Alfred swi&thorn;e wel,</L><L N="1270">and his worde was Goddspel, <PB N="108"></L><L>&thorn;at "euereuch man, &thorn;e bet him beo,</L><L>eauer &thorn;e bet he hine beseo:"</L><L>"ne truste no mon to his weole</L><L>to swi&thorn;e, &thorn;ah he habbe ueole."</L><L N="1275">"Nis [nout] so hot &thorn;at hit nacole&thorn;,</L><L>ne no&yogh;t so hwit &thorn;at hit ne sole&thorn;,</L><L>ne no&yogh;t so leof &thorn;at hit ne alo&thorn;e&thorn;,</L><L>ne no&yogh;t so glad &thorn;at hit ne awro&thorn;e&thorn;:</L><L>ac eauereeu[c]h &thorn;ing &thorn;at eche nis,</L><L N="1280">agon schal, &amp; al &thorn;is worldes blis."</L><L>Nu &thorn;u mi&yogh;t wite readliche,</L><L>&thorn;at eauere &thorn;u spekest gideliche:</L><L>for al &thorn;at &thorn;u me seist for schame,</L><L>euer &thorn;e seolue hit turne&thorn; to grome.</L><L N="1285">Go so hit go, at eche fenge</L><L>&thorn;u fallest mid &thorn;ine ahene swenge;</L><L>al &thorn;at &thorn;u seist for me to schende,</L><L>hit is mi wurschipe at &thorn;an ende.</L><L>Bute &thorn;u wille bet aginne,</L><L N="1290">ne shaltu bute schame iwinne."</L><L>   &THORN;e ni&yogh;tingale sat &amp; si&yogh;te,</L><L>&amp; hohful was, &amp; ful wel mi&yogh;te,</L><L>for &thorn;e hule swo ispeke hadde, 
<MILESTONE N="242v.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>an hire speche swo iladde.</L><L N="1295">Heo was ho[h]ful, &amp; erede</L><L>hwat heo &thorn;arafter hire sede: <PB N="110"></L><L>ah neo&thorn;eles heo hire understod.</L><L>" Wat!" heo seide, "hule, artu wod?</L><L>&thorn;u &yogh;eolpest of seolliche wisdome,</L><L N="1300">&thorn;u nustest wanene he &thorn;e come,</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 1301 through 1400</HEAD><L>bute hit of wicchecrefte were.</L><L>&THORN;arof &thorn;u, wrecche, mos[t] &thorn;e skere</L><L>&yogh;if &thorn;u wult among manne b[eo]:</L><L>o&thorn;er &thorn;u most of londe fleo.</L><L N="1305">For alle &thorn;eo &thorn;at [&thorn;]erof cu&thorn;e,</L><L>heo uere ifurn of prestes mu&thorn;e</L><L>amanset: swuch &thorn;u art &yogh;ette,</L><L>&thorn;u wiecche-crafte neauer ne lete.</L><L>Ich &thorn;e seide nu lutel ere,</L><L N="1310">an &thorn;u askedest &yogh;ef ich were</L><L>a-bisemere to preost ihoded.</L><L>Ah &thorn;e mansing is so ibroded,</L><L>&thorn;ah no preost a-londe nere,</L><L>a wrecche neo&thorn;eles &thorn;u were:</L><L N="1315">for eauereuch chil[d] &thorn;e cleope&thorn; fule,</L><L>an euereuch man a wrecche hule.</L><L>Ich habbe iherd, &amp; so&thorn; hit is,</L><L>&thorn;e mon mot beo wel storre-wis,</L><L>[&thorn;at] wite inno[h] of wucche &thorn;inge kume,</L><L N="1320">so &thorn;u seist &thorn;[e] is iwune. <PB N="112"></L><L>Hwat canstu, wrecche &thorn;ing, of storre,</L><L>bute &thorn;at &thorn;u biha[u]est hi feorre?</L><L>Alswo de&thorn; mani dor &amp; man,</L><L>&thorn;eo of [swucche] nawiht ne con.</L><L N="1325">On ape mai a boc bih[o]lde,</L><L>an leues wenden &amp; eft folde:</L><L>ac he ne con &thorn;e bet &thorn;aruore 
<MILESTONE N="242v.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>of clerkes lore top ne more.</L><L>&THORN;ah &thorn;u iseo &thorn;e steorre alsw[o],</L><L N="1330">nartu &thorn;e wisure neauer &thorn;e mo.</L><L>Ah &yogh;et &thorn;u, fule &thorn;ing, me chist,</L><L>an wel grimliche me atwist</L><L>&thorn;at ich singe bi manne huse,</L><L>an teache wif breke spuse.</L><L N="1335">&THORN;u liest iwis, &thorn;u fule &thorn;ing!</L><L>&thorn;[urh] me nas neauer ischend spusing.</L><L>Ah so&thorn; hit is ich singe &amp; grede</L><L>&thorn;ar lauedies beo&thorn; &amp; faire maide;</L><L>&amp; so&thorn; hit is of luue ich singe:</L><L N="1340">for god wif mai i[n] spusing <PB N="114"></L><L>bet luuien hire o&yogh;ene were,</L><L>&thorn;ane awe[r] hire copenere;</L><L>an maide mai luue cheose</L><L>&thorn;at hire wur&thorn;schipe ne forleose,</L><L N="1345">an luuie mid rihte luue</L><L>&thorn;ane &thorn;e schal beon hire buue.</L><L>Swiche luue ich itache &amp; lere,</L><L>&thorn;erof beo&thorn; al mine ibere.</L><L>&THORN;ah sum wif beo of nesche mode,</L><L N="1350">for wumm[e]n beo&thorn; of softe blode,</L><L>&thorn;at heo, &thorn;urh sume sottes lore</L><L>&thorn;e &yogh;eorne bit &amp; sike&thorn; sore,</L><L>mis[r]empe &amp; misdo sumne stunde,</L><L>schal ich &thorn;aruore beon ibunde ?</L><L N="1355">&YOGH;if wimmen luuie&thorn; unrede,</L><L>[w]itestu me hore misdede?</L><L>&YOGH;ef wimmon &thorn;enche&thorn; luuie derne,</L><L>[ne] mai ich mine songes werne.</L><L>Wummon mai pleie under clo&thorn;e,</L><L N="1360">we&thorn;er heo wile, wel &thorn;e wro&thorn;e:</L><L>&amp; heo mai do bi mine songe, 
<MILESTONE N="243r.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>hwa&thorn;er heo wule, wel &thorn;e wronge.</L><L>For nis a-worlde &thorn;ing so god,</L><L>&thorn;at ne mai do sum ungod,</L><L N="1365">&yogh;if me hit wule turne amis.</L><L>For gold &amp; seoluer, god hit is:</L><L>an no&thorn;eles &thorn;armid &thorn;u mi&yogh;t</L><L>spusbruche buggen &amp; unri&yogh;t.</L><L>Wepne beo&thorn; gode gri&thorn; to halde:</L><L N="1370">ah neo&thorn;eles &thorn;armide beo&thorn; men acwalde <PB N="116"></L><L>a&yogh;eines riht [an] fale londe,</L><L>&thorn;ar &thorn;eoues hi bere&eth; an honde.</L><L>Alswa hit is bi mine songe,</L><L>&thorn;ah heo beo god, me hine mai misfonge,</L><L N="1375">an drahe hine to sothede,</L><L>an to o&thorn;re uuele dede.</L><L>Ah [schaltu] wrecch, luue tele ?</L><L>Bo wuch ho bo, vich luue is fele</L><L>bitweone wepmon &amp; wimmane:</L><L N="1380">ah &yogh;ef heo is atbroide, &thorn;enne</L><L>he is unfele &amp; forbrode.</L><L>Wro&thorn; wur&thorn;e heom &thorn;e holi rode</L><L>&thorn;e rihte ikunde swo forbreide&thorn;!</L><L>W[u]nder hit is &thorn;at heo nawede&thorn;.</L><L N="1385">An swo heo do&thorn;, for heo beo&thorn; wode</L><L>&thorn;e bute nest go&thorn; to brode.</L><L>Wummon is of nesche flesche,</L><L>an flesches [lust] is strong to cwesse:</L><L>nis wunder nan &thorn;ah he abide.</L><L N="1390">For flesches lustes hi make&thorn; slide,</L><L>ne beo&thorn; heo nowt alle forlore,</L><L>&thorn;at stumpe&thorn; at &thorn;e flesches more:</L><L>for moni wummon haue&thorn; misdo</L><L>&thorn;at aris[t] op of &thorn;e slo.</L><L N="1395">Ne beo&thorn; nowt ones alle sunne, 
<MILESTONE N="243r.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>for&thorn;an hi beo&thorn; tweire kunne: <PB N="118"></L><L>su[m] arist of &thorn;e flesches luste,</L><L>an sum of &thorn;e gostes custe.</L><L>&THORN;ar flesch drahe&thorn; men to drunnesse,</L><L N="1400">an to [wrouehede] &amp; to golnesse,</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 1401 through 1500</HEAD><L>&thorn;e gost misde&thorn; &thorn;urch ni&thorn;e an onde,</L><L>&amp; seo&thorn;&thorn;e mid murh&thorn;e of [monne shonde,] <PB N="120"></L><L>an &yogh;eone&thorn; after more &amp; more,</L><L>an lutel reh&thorn; of milce &amp; ore ;</L><L N="1405">an sti&yogh;&thorn; on he[h] &thorn;ur[h] modinesse,</L><L>an ouerhohe&eth; &thorn;anne lasse.</L><L>Sei [me soo&thorn;], &yogh;ef &thorn;u hit wost,</L><L>hwe&thorn;er de&thorn; wurse, flesch &thorn;e gost?</L><L>&THORN;u mi&yogh;t segge, &yogh;ef &thorn;u wult,</L><L N="1410">&thorn;at lasse is &thorn;e flesches gult:</L><L>moni man is of his flesche clene,</L><L>&thorn;at is mid mode deouel-imene.</L><L>Ne schal non mon wimman bigrede,</L><L>an flesches lustes hire upbreide:</L><L N="1415">swuch he may te[l]en of golnesse,</L><L>&thorn;at sunege&thorn; wurse i[n] modinesse.</L><L>[&YOGH;]et &yogh;if ich schulde a-luue bringe</L><L>wif o&thorn;er maide, hwanne ich singe,</L><L>ich wolde wi&thorn; &thorn;e maide holde,</L><L N="1420">&yogh;if &thorn;u hit const ariht atholde:</L><L>Lust nu, ich segge &thorn;e hwaruore,</L><L>vp to &thorn;e toppe from &thorn;e more.</L><L>&YOGH;ef maide luue&thorn; dernliche,</L><L>heo stumpe&thorn; &amp; fal&thorn; icundeliche:</L><L N="1425">for &thorn;ah heo sum hwile pleie,</L><L>heo nis nout feor ut of &thorn;e weie;</L><L>heo mai hire guld atwende</L><L>a rihte weie &thorn;ur[h] chirche-bende,</L><L>an mai eft habbe to make 
<MILESTONE N="243v.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L N="1430">hire leofmon wi&thorn;ute sake,     <PB N="122"></L><L>an go to him bi daies lihte,</L><L>&thorn;at er stal to bi &thorn;eostre nihte.</L><L>An &yogh;unling not hwat swuch &thorn;ing is:</L><L>his &yogh;unge blod hit dra&yogh;e&thorn; amis,</L><L N="1435">an sum sot mon hit tih&thorn; &thorn;arto</L><L>mid alle &thorn;an &thorn;at he mai do.</L><L>He come&thorn; &amp; fare&thorn; &amp; beod &amp; bi[t]</L><L>an heo bistant &amp; ouersi[t],</L><L>an biseh&thorn; ilome &amp; longe.</L><L N="1440">Hwat mai &thorn;at chil[d] &thorn;ah hit misfonge?</L><L>Hit nuste neauer hwat hit was,</L><L>for&thorn;i hit &thorn;ohte fondi [&thorn;]as,</L><L>an wite iwis hwuch beo &thorn;e gome</L><L>&thorn;at of so wilde make&thorn; tome.</L><L N="1445">Ne mai ich for reo[w]e lete,</L><L>wanne ich iseo &thorn;e tohte ilete</L><L>&thorn;e luue bring[e] on &thorn;e &yogh;unglinge,</L><L>&thorn;at ich of mur&yogh;&thorn;e him ne singe.</L><L>Ich [t]eache heom bi mine songe</L><L N="1450">&thorn;at swucch luue ne lest no&yogh;t longe:</L><L>for mi song lutle hwile ilest,</L><L>an luue ne de&thorn; no&yogh;t bute rest <PB N="124"></L><L>on swuch childre, &amp; sone age&thorn;,</L><L>an fal&thorn; adun &thorn;e hote bre&thorn;.</L><L N="1455">Ich singe mid heom one &thorn;ro&yogh;e,</L><L>biginne on heh &amp; endi la&yogh;e,</L><L>an lete [mine] songes falle</L><L>an lutle wile adun mid alle.</L><L>&THORN;at maide wot, hwanne ich swike,</L><L N="1460">&thorn;at luue is mine songes ili[k]e,</L><L>for hit nis bute a lutel bre&thorn;,</L><L>&thorn;at sone kume&thorn;, &amp; sone ge&thorn;.</L><L>&THORN;at child bi me hit understond, 
<MILESTONE N="243v.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>an his unred to red[e] wend,</L><L N="1465">an ise&yogh;&thorn; wel, bi mine songe,</L><L>&thorn;at dusi luue ne last no&yogh;t longe.</L><L>Ah wel ich wule &thorn;at &thorn;u hit wite,</L><L>lo&thorn; me beo&thorn; wiues utschute:</L><L>ah [w]if mai [of] me nime &yogh;eme,</L><L N="1470">ich ne singe nawt hwan ich teme.</L><L>An wif ah lete so[t]tes lore,</L><L>&thorn;ah spusing-bendes &thorn;unche&thorn; sore.</L><L>Wundere me &thorn;ung&thorn; wel starc &amp; stor,</L><L>hu eni mon so eauar for,</L><L N="1475">&thorn;at [h]e his heorte mi&yogh;te driue</L><L>[to] do hit to o&thorn;ers mannes wiue:</L><L>for o&thorn;er hit is of twam &thorn;inge,</L><L>ne mai &thorn;at &thorn;ridde no man bringe;</L><L>o[&thorn;]ar &thorn;e lauerd is wel aht,</L><L N="1480">o&thorn;er aswunde, &amp; nis naht.</L><L>&YOGH;ef he is wur&thorn;ful &amp; aht man,</L><L>nele no man, &thorn;at wisdo[m] can, <PB N="126"></L><L>hure of is wiue do him schame:</L><L>for he mai him adrede grame,</L><L N="1485">an &thorn;at he forleose &thorn;at &thorn;er honge&thorn;,</L><L>&thorn;at him eft &thorn;arto no&yogh;t ne longe&thorn;.</L><L>An &thorn;ah he &thorn;at no&yogh;t ne adrede,</L><L>hit is unri&yogh;t &amp; gret sothede</L><L>[to] misdon one gode manne,</L><L N="1490">an his ibedde from him spanne.</L><L>&YOGH;ef hire lauerd is forwurde</L><L>an unorne at bedde &amp; at borde,</L><L>hu mi&yogh;te &thorn;ar beo eni luue</L><L>wanne [a] cheorles buc hire ley buue?</L><L N="1495">Hu mai &thorn;ar eni luue beo,</L><L>war swuch man grope&thorn; hire &thorn;eo?</L><L>Herbi &thorn;u mi&yogh;t wel understonde 
<MILESTONE N="244r.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>&thorn;at on [is a reu], &thorn;at o&thorn;er schonde,</L><L>to stele to o&thorn;res mannes bedde.</L><L N="1500">For &yogh;if aht man is hire bedde,</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 1501 through 1600</HEAD><L>&thorn;u mi&yogh;t wene &thorn;at &thorn;e mistide,</L><L>wanne &thorn;u list bi hire side.</L><L>An &yogh;ef &thorn;e lauerd is a w[re]cche,</L><L>hwuch este mi&yogh;tistu &thorn;ar uecche? <PB N="128"></L><L N="1505">&YOGH;if &thorn;u bi&thorn;enchest hwo hire ofligge,</L><L>&thorn;u mi&yogh;t mid wlate &thorn;e este bugge.</L><L>Ich not hu mai eni freo-man</L><L>for hire sechen after &thorn;an.</L><L>&YOGH;ef he bi&thorn;enc&thorn; bi hwan he lai,</L><L N="1510">al mai &thorn;e luue gan awai."</L><L>   &THORN;e hule was glad of swuche tale:</L><L>heo &thorn;o&yogh;te &thorn;at te nihtegale,</L><L>&thorn;ah heo wel speke atte frume,</L><L>hadde at &thorn;en ende misnume :</L><L N="1515">an seide: "Nu ich habbe ifunde</L><L>&thorn;at maidenes beo&thorn; of &thorn;ine imunde:</L><L>mid heom &thorn;u holdest, &amp; heom biwerest,</L><L>an ouerswi&thorn;e &thorn;u hi herest.</L><L>&THORN;e lauedies beo&thorn; to me iwend,</L><L N="1520">to me heo hire mo[n]e send.</L><L>For hit itit ofte &amp; ilome,</L><L>&thorn;at wif &amp; were beo&thorn; unisome:</L><L>&amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;e were gulte,</L><L>&thorn;at leof is over wummon to pulte,</L><L N="1525">an spene&thorn; on &thorn;are al &thorn;at he haue&thorn;,</L><L>an siue&thorn; &thorn;are &thorn;at no riht naue&thorn;, <PB N="130"></L><L>an haue&thorn; attom his ri&yogh;te spuse,</L><L>wowes weste, &amp; lere huse,</L><L>wel &thorn;unne isch[r]ud &amp; iued wro&thorn;e,</L><L N="1530">an let heo bute mete &amp; clo&thorn;e.</L><L>Wan he come&thorn; ham eft to his wiue, 
<MILESTONE N="244r.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>ne dar heo no&yogh;t a word ischire:</L><L>he chid &amp; gred swuch he beo wod,</L><L>an ne bring&thorn; [hom] non o&thorn;er god.</L><L N="1535">Al &thorn;at heo de&thorn; him is unwille,</L><L>al &thorn;at heo speke&thorn; hit is him ille:</L><L>an oft hwan heo no&yogh;t ne misde&thorn;,</L><L>heo haue&thorn; &thorn;e fust in hire te&thorn;.</L><L>&THORN;[er] is nan mon &thorn;at ne mai ibringe</L><L N="1540">his wif amis mid swucche &thorn;inge:</L><L>me hire mai so ofte misbeode,</L><L>&thorn;at heo do wule hire ahene neode.</L><L>La, Godd hit wot! heo nah iweld,</L><L>&thorn;a[h] heo hine makie kukeweld.</L><L N="1545">For hit itit lome &amp; ofte,</L><L>&thorn;at his wif is wel nesche &amp; softe,</L><L>of faire bleo &amp; wel idiht:</L><L>[For]&thorn;i hit is &thorn;e more unriht</L><L>&thorn;at he his luue spene on &thorn;are,</L><L N="1550">&thorn;at nis wur&thorn; one of hire heare.</L><L>An swucche men beo&thorn; wel manifolde,</L><L>&thorn;at wif ne kunne no&yogh;t ari&yogh;t holde.</L><L>Ne mot non mon wi&thorn; hire speke:</L><L>he uene&eth; heo wule anon tobreke</L><L N="1555">hire spusing, &yogh;ef heo loke&thorn;</L><L>o&thorn;er wi&thorn; manne faire speke&thorn;. <PB N="132"></L><L>He hire bilu[k]&thorn; mid keie &amp; loke:</L><L>&thorn;ar-&thorn;urh is spusing ofte tobroke.</L><L>For &yogh;ef heo is &thorn;arto ibroht,</L><L N="1560">he de&thorn; &thorn;at heo nadde ear i&thorn;oht.</L><L>Dahet &thorn;at to swu&thorn;e hit bispeke,</L><L>&thorn;ah swucche wiues [heom] awreke !</L><L>Herof &thorn;e lauedies to me mene&thorn;,</L><L>an wel sore me ahwene&thorn;:</L><L N="1565">wel neh min heorte wule tochine, 
<MILESTONE N="244v.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>hwon ich biholde hire pine.</L><L>Mid heom ich wepe swi[&thorn;]e sore,</L><L>an for heom bidde Cristis ore,</L><L>&thorn;at &thorn;e lauedi sone aredde</L><L N="1570">an hire sende betere ibedde.</L><L>An o&thorn;er &thorn;ing ich mai &thorn;e telle,</L><L>&thorn;at &thorn;u ne schal[t], for &thorn;ine felle,</L><L>ondswere none &thorn;arto finde:</L><L>al &thorn;i sputing schal aswinde.</L><L N="1575">Moni chapmon &amp; moni cniht</L><L>luue&thorn; &amp; [hald] his wif ariht,</L><L>an swa de&thorn; moni bondeman:</L><L>&thorn;at gode wif de&thorn; after &thorn;an,</L><L>an serue&thorn; him to bedde &amp; to borde</L><L N="1580">mid faire dede &amp; faire worde,</L><L>an &yogh;eorne fonde&thorn; hu heo muhe</L><L>do &thorn;ing &thorn;at him beo idu&yogh;e.</L><L>&THORN;e lauerd into &thorn;are [&thorn;]eode</L><L>fare&thorn; ut on &thorn;are beire nede,</L><L N="1585">an is &thorn;at gode wif unbli&thorn;e</L><L>for hire lauerdes hou[h]si&thorn;e, <PB N="134"></L><L>an sit &amp; sih&eth; wel sore oflonged,</L><L>an hire sore an horte ongred:</L><L>al for hire louerdes sake</L><L N="1590">haue&thorn; daies kare &amp; ni&yogh;tes wake:</L><L>an swu&thorn;e longe hire is &thorn;e hwile,</L><L>an [ech] steape hire &thorn;un&thorn; a mile.</L><L>Hwanne o&thorn;re slepe&thorn; hire abute,</L><L>ich one lust &thorn;ar wi&&thorn;ute,</L><L N="1595">an wot of hire sore mode,</L><L>an singe ani&yogh;t for hire gode:</L><L>an mine gode song, for hire &thorn;inge,</L><L>ich turne su[m]del to murni[n]ge.</L><L>Of hure seorhe ich bere sume, 
<MILESTONE N="244v.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L N="1600">for&thorn;an ich am hire wel welcume:   </L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 1601 through 1700</HEAD><L>ich hire helpe hwat [I] mai,</L><L>for [ho ge&thorn;] &thorn;ane rehte wai.</L><L>Ah &thorn;u me hauest sore igramed,</L><L>&thorn;at min heorte is wel neh alamed,</L><L N="1605">&thorn;at ich mai unnea&thorn;e speke:</L><L>ah &yogh;et ich wule for&thorn;ure reke.</L><L>&THORN;u seist &thorn;at ich am manne [lo&],</L><L>an euereuch man is wi&eth; me wro&eth;,</L><L>an me mid stone &amp; lugge &thorn;rete&thorn;,</L><L N="1610">an me tobu[r]ste&thorn; &amp; tobete&thorn;, <PB N="136"></L><L>an hwanne heo hab[b]e&thorn; me ofslahe,</L><L>heo honge&thorn; me on heore hahe,</L><L>&thorn;ar ich aschewele pie an crowe</L><L>fro[m] &thorn;an &thorn;e &thorn;ar is isowe.</L><L N="1615">&THORN;ah hit beo so&thorn;, ich do heom god,</L><L>an for heom ich [s]chadde mi blod:</L><L>ich do heom god mid mine dea&thorn;e,</L><L>waruore &thorn;e is wel unnea&thorn;e.</L><L>For &thorn;ah &thorn;u ligge dead &amp; clinge,</L><L N="1620">&thorn;i de&thorn; nis nawt to none &thorn;inge:</L><L>ich not neauer to hwan &thorn;u mi&yogh;t,</L><L>for &thorn;u nart bute a wrecche wi&yogh;t.</L><L>Ah &thorn;ah mi lif me beo atschote,</L><L>&thorn;e &yogh;et ich mai do gode note:</L><L N="1625">me mai up one smale sticke</L><L>me sette a-wude ine &thorn;e &thorn;icke,</L><L>an swa mai mon tolli him to</L><L>lutle briddes &amp; iuo,</L><L>an swa me mai mid me bi&yogh;ete</L><L N="1630">wel gode brede to his mete.</L><L>Ah &thorn;u neure mon to gode</L><L>liues ne dea&thorn;es stal ne stode: <PB N="138"></L><L>ich not to hwan &thorn;u bre[d]ist &thorn;i brod, 
<MILESTONE N="245r.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>liues ne dea&thorn;es ne de&thorn; hit god."</L><L N="1635">   &THORN;e nihtegale ih[e]rde &thorn;is,</L><L>an hupte uppon on blowe ris,</L><L>an herre sat &thorn;an heo dude ear:</L><L>"Hule," he seide, "beo nu wear,</L><L>nulle ich wi&thorn; &thorn;e plaidi namore,</L><L N="1640">for her &thorn;e mist &thorn;i rihte lore:</L><L>&thorn;u &yogh;eilpest &thorn;at &thorn;u art manne lo&thorn;,</L><L>an euereuch wiht is wi&eth; &thorn;e w[ro]&thorn;;</L><L>an mid &yogh;ulinge &amp; mid igrede</L><L>&thorn;u wanst wel &thorn;at &thorn;u art unlede.</L><L N="1645">&THORN;u seist &thorn;at gromes &thorn;e ifo&eth;,</L><L>an heie on rodde &thorn;e anho&eth;,</L><L>an &thorn;e totwichet &amp; toschake&eth;,</L><L>an summe of &thorn;e schawles make&eth;.</L><L>Me &thorn;unc[&thorn;] &thorn;at &thorn;u forleost &thorn;at game,</L><L N="1650">&thorn;u &yogh;ulpest of &thorn;ire o&yogh;e schame:</L><L>me &thorn;unc[&thorn;] &thorn;at &thorn;u me gest an honde,</L><L>&thorn;u &yogh;ulpest of &thorn;ire o&yogh;ene scho[nd]e."</L><L>&THORN;o heo hadde &thorn;eos word icwede,</L><L>heo sat in ore faire stude,</L><L N="1655">an &thorn;arafter hire steuene dihte,</L><L>an song so schille &amp; so brihte, <PB N="140"></L><L>&thorn;at feor &amp; ner me hit iherde.</L><L>&THORN;aruore anan to hire cherde</L><L>&thorn;rusche &amp; &thorn;rostle &amp; wudewale,</L><L N="1660">an fuheles bo&thorn;e grete &amp; smale:</L><L>for&thorn;an heom &thorn;uhte &thorn;at heo hadde</L><L>&thorn;e houle ouercome, uor&thorn;an heo gradde</L><L>an sungen alswa uale wise,</L><L>an blisse was among &thorn;e rise.</L><L N="1665">Ri&yogh;t swa me gred &thorn;e manne a schame,</L><L>&thorn;at tauele&thorn; &amp; forleost &thorn;at gome.</L><L>   &THORN;eos hule, &thorn;o heo &thorn;is iherde, 
<MILESTONE N="245r.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>"Hauestu," heo seide, "ibanned ferde ?</L><L>an wultu, wreche, wi&eth; me fi&yogh;te?</L><L N="1670">Nai! nai! nauestu none mi&yogh;te!</L><L>Hwat grede&thorn; &thorn;eo &thorn;at hider come?</L><L>Me &thorn;unc&thorn; &thorn;u ledest ferde to me.</L><L>&YOGH;e schule wite, ar &yogh;e fleo heonne,</L><L>hwuch is &thorn;e stren&thorn;e of mine kunne:</L><L N="1675">for &thorn;eo &thorn;e haue&thorn; bile ihoked,</L><L>an cliures [s]charpe &amp; wel icroked,</L><L>alle heo beo&thorn; of mine kunrede,</L><L>an walde come &yogh;if ich bede. <PB N="142"></L><L>&THORN;e seolfe coc, &thorn;at wel can fi&yogh;te,</L><L N="1680">he mot mid me holde mid ri&yogh;te,</L><L>for [bo&thorn;e] we habbe&thorn; steuene bri&yogh;te,</L><L>an sitte&thorn; under weolcne bi ni&yogh;te.</L><L>Schille ich an utest uppen ow grede,</L><L>ich shal swo stronge ferde lede,</L><L N="1685">&thorn;at ower pr[u]de schal aualle:</L><L>a tort ne &yogh;iue ich for ow alle!</L><L>ne schal, ar hit beo fulliche eue,</L><L>a wreche fe&thorn;er on ow bileaue.</L><L>Ah hit was unker uoreward,</L><L N="1690">&thorn;o we come hiderward,</L><L>&thorn;at we &thorn;arto holde scholde,</L><L>&thorn;ar riht dom us &yogh;iue wolde.</L><L>Wultu nu breke foreward?</L><L>Ich wene dom &thorn;e &thorn;ing[&thorn;] to hard:</L><L N="1695">for &thorn;u ne darst domes abide,</L><L>&thorn;u wult nu, wreche, fi&yogh;te &amp; chide.</L><L>&YOGH;[u]t ich ow alle wolde rede,</L><L>ar [ich] utheste uppon ow grede, <PB N="144"></L><L>&thorn;at ower fihtlac lete&thorn; beo,</L><L N="1700">an ginne&thorn; ra&thorn;e awei fleo.</L><L>For, bi &thorn;e cliures &thorn;at ich bere, 
<MILESTONE N="245v.1" UNIT="folio"></L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 1701 through 1794</HEAD><L>&yogh;ef &yogh;e abide&thorn; mine here,</L><L>&yogh;e schule on o&thorn;er wise singe,</L><L>an acursi alle fi&yogh;tinge :</L><L N="1705">vor nis of ow non so kene,</L><L>&thorn;at durre abide mine onsene."</L><L>&THORN;eos hule spac wel baldeliche,</L><L>for &thorn;ah heo nadde swo hwatliche</L><L>ifare after hire here,</L><L N="1710">heo walde neo&thorn;eles &yogh;efe answere</L><L>&thorn;e ni&yogh;tegale mid swucche worde.</L><L>For moni man mid speres orde</L><L>haue&thorn; lutle strenc&thorn;e, &amp; mid his [s]chelde,</L><L>ah neo&thorn;eles in one felde,</L><L N="1715">&thorn;urh belde worde an mid ilete,</L><L>de&thorn; his iuo for areh&thorn;e swete.</L><L>&THORN;e wranne, for heo cu&thorn;e singe,</L><L>&thorn;ar com in &thorn;are more&yogh;en[i]nge</L><L>to helpe &thorn;are ni&yogh;tegale:</L><L N="1720">for &thorn;ah heo hadde steuene smale,</L><L>heo hadde gode &thorn;[ro]te &amp; schille,</L><L>an fale manne song a wille.</L><L>&THORN;e wranne was wel wis iholde,</L><L>vor &thorn;e&yogh; heo nere ibred a-wolde,</L><L N="1725">ho was ito&yogh;en among man[k]enne,</L><L>an hire wisdom brohte &thorn;enne:</L><L>heo mi&yogh;te speke hwar heo walde,</L><L>touore &thorn;e king &thorn;ah heo scholde. <PB N="146"></L><L>"Luste&thorn;," heo cwa&thorn;, "late&thorn; me speke.</L><L N="1730">Hwat! wulle &yogh;e &thorn;is pes tobreke,</L><L>an do &thorn;anne [kinge] swuch schame?</L><L>&YOGH;e[t] nis he nou&thorn;er ded ne lame.</L><L>Hunke schal itide harm &amp; schonde,</L><L>&yogh;ef &yogh;e do&thorn; gri&thorn;bruche on his londe.</L><L N="1735">Late&thorn; beo, &amp; beo&thorn; isome, 
<MILESTONE N="245v.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>an fare&thorn; riht to o[w]er dome,</L><L>an late&thorn; dom &thorn;is plaid tobreke,</L><L>al swo hit was erur bispeke."</L><L>   "Ich an wel," cwa&eth; &thorn;e ni&yogh;tegale,</L><L N="1740">"ah, wranne, nawt for &thorn;ire tale,</L><L>ah do for mire lahfulnesse.</L><L>Ich nolde &thorn;at unrihtfulnesse</L><L>me at &thorn;en ende ouerkome:</L><L>ich nam ofdrad of none dome.</L><L N="1745">Bihote ich habbe, so&thorn; hit is,</L><L>&thorn;at Maister Nichole, &thorn;at is wis,</L><L>bituxen vs deme schul[l]e,</L><L>an &yogh;e[t] ich wene &thorn;at he wule.</L><L>Ah, [w]ar mihte we hine finde?"</L><L N="1750">&THORN;e wranne sat in ore linde; <PB N="148"></L><L>"Hwat! nu[s]te &yogh;e," cwa&thorn; heo, "his hom?</L><L>He wune&thorn; at Porteshom,</L><L>at one tune ine Dorsete,</L><L>bi &thorn;are see in ore utlete:</L><L N="1755">&thorn;ar he deme&thorn; manie ri&yogh;te dom,</L><L>an diht &amp; writ mani wisdom,</L><L>an &thorn;urh his mu&thorn;e &amp; &thorn;urh his honde</L><L>hit is &thorn;e betere into Scotlonde,</L><L>To seche hine is lihtlich &thorn;ing;</L><L N="1760">he naue&thorn; bute one woning.</L><L>&THORN;at [is] bischopen muchel schame,</L><L>an alle [&thorn;]an &thorn;at of his nome</L><L>habbe&thorn; ihert, &amp; of his dede.</L><L>Hwi nulle&thorn; hi nimen heom to rede,</L><L N="1765">&thorn;at he were mid heom ilome</L><L>for teche heom of his wisdome,</L><L>an &yogh;iue him rente auale stude,</L><L>&thorn;at he mi&yogh;te heom ilome be mide?" <PB N="150"></L><L>   "Certes," cwa&thorn; &thorn;e hule, "&thorn;at is so&eth;: 
<MILESTONE N="246r.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L N="1770">&thorn;eos riche men wel muche misdo&eth;,</L><L>&thorn;at lete&thorn; &thorn;ane gode mon,</L><L>&thorn;at of so feole &thorn;inge con,</L><L>an &yogh;iue&thorn; rente wel misliche,</L><L>an of him lete&thorn; wel lihtliche.</L><L N="1775">Wi&eth; heore cunne heo beo&thorn; mildre,</L><L>au &yogh;eue&thorn; rente litle childre:</L><L>swo heore wit hi dem&thorn; adwole,</L><L>&thorn;ut euer abid Maistre Nichole.</L><L>Ah ute we &thorn;ah to him fare,</L><L N="1780">for &thorn;ar is unker dom al &yogh;are."</L><L>   "Do we" &thorn;e ni&yogh;tegale seide:</L><L>"ah [w]a schal unker speche rede,</L><L>an telle touore unker deme ?"</L><L>   "&THORN;arof ich schal &thorn;e wel icweme,"</L><L N="1785">cwa&thorn; &thorn;e houle; "for al, ende of orde,</L><L>telle ich con, word after worde:</L><L>an &yogh;ef &thorn;e &thorn;inc&thorn; &thorn;at ich misrempe,</L><L>&thorn;u stond a&yogh;ein &amp; do me crempe."</L><L>Mid &thorn;isse worde for&thorn; hi ferden,</L><L N="1790">al bute here &amp; bute uerde,</L><L>to Portesham &thorn;at heo bicome.</L><L>Ah hu heo spedde of heore dome,</L><L>ne [c]an ich eu namore telle:</L><L>her nis namore of &thorn;is spelle.</L></DIV1></BODY></TEXT></TEI.2>